<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Takes Title of Euro 2000 with Golden Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ROTTERDAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- David Trezeguet scored the "
golden goal" to gave France a strong comback victory over Italy on
Sunday when the world champion also won the European championship.
</P>
<P>
France's Sylvain Wiltord grabbed a dramatic last minute
equalizer for France in the the fourth minute of injury time,
another substitute David Trezeguet volleyed the winner home in the
103rd minute.
</P>
<P>
Italy went ahead in the 56th minute when Gianluca Pessotto
curled a low cross into the area and Delvecchio stabbed it home
with the inside of his left foot high into the nets and outside
Fabien Barthez' reach.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 European Championship was also decided on a golden
goal when Germany beat the Czech Republic 2-1.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time in a row that France came back from a
goal down. It also beat Spain and Portugal by the same score in
the quarter- and semifinals.
</P>
<P>
When all seemed lost, Wiltord finally found a hole in the
ironclad Italian defense and beat Francesco Toldo with a low
angled shot.
</P>
<P>
With France pushing ever harder, Robert Pires broke on the
left and passed low into the path of Trezeguet, who volleyed high
into the net from 10 meters out.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody thought we were dead," said Thierry Henry. "With
the French team, it is never over."
</P>
<P>
France thus became the first nation to win a European
championship title as a world champion.
</P>
<P>
Didier Deschamps, in his 101st international appearance held
the trophy aloft wildly cheered on by some 10,000 French fans,
French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
in the sellout crowd of 48,000 at De Kuip.
</P>
<P>
Italian coach Dino Zoff had been a minute away from becoming
the first man to win the European championship both as coach and
player when Wiltord equalized.
</P>
<P>
With Italy leading in regulation time, substitute Alessandro
Del Piero should have put the game away twice but first he was off
target and in the 84th minute, Barthez did well to cover the shot.
</P>
<P>
From the first minute, the final was spectacular. Thierry
Henry already showed off his speed, outpacing Mark Iuliano and
sending a dangerous cross into the center, where no Frenchman was
able to pick it up. Henry would trouble the Italian defense with
his pace all through the final.
</P>
<P>
Italy responded, sending Delvecchio deep and forcing Barthez
to scurry out of his box and clear.
</P>
<P>
In the 5th minute, Henry surprised everyone hooking a volley
from a narrow angle from 14 meters out and Toldo was lucky to see
it bounce off the near post.
</P>
<P>
The seesaw battle continued and three minutes later, Stefano
Fiore exposed the flank of Bixente Lizarazu and floated a cross
into the middle but Delvecchio came centimeters short to connect
and volley from close range.
</P>
<P>
In the second half, Henry continued to dumbfound the Italian
defense with his lightning speed. From the left side, he rolled up
the defense in the 50th minute but unfortunately no one was there
when his pass rolled unchallenged into the goalmouth.
</P>
<P>
Zoff brought in Del Piero in the 53rd minute and suddenly
Italy three players on the pitch with a nose for goal, together
with Francesco Totti and Delvecchio.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came only minutes later.
</P>
<P>
From then on, Italians could rely on the counter and they
relished it.
</P>
<P>
At the back, the defense proved as fullproof as expected with
Alessandro Nesta and Cannavaro giving true leadership.
</P>
<P>
After the goal, things got rougher and Lilian Thuram got
France's first yellow card for a tackle on Totti.
</P>
<P>
Wiltord shot straight at Toldo in the 62nd minute when an
unmarked Djorkaeff shoot begging for the ball in front of goal.
Wiltord was luckier in the 93rd minute.
</P>
<P>
In extra time, France took the early initiative and when
Robert Pires drilled a ball straight at Toldo and when David
Trezeguet followed up for the rebound, he kicked the Italian
goalie a bloody noze.
</P>
<P>
"The French were stronger tonight. I feel very bad. We had a
lot of opportunities to score and you can't say we didn't put up a
fight," Italian coach Dino Zoff said. Enitem
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
