<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris Celebrates France's Victory in Euro 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Paris exploded with a chorus of
hollers, honks and whoops Sunday night as the French took to the
streets in a frenzied celebration after the 2-1 triumph of their
team over Italy in the Euro 2000 soccer final, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Security was tight on the Champs-Elysees, where the crowds of
joyous revelers brought to mind the massive national pride that
turned Paris into a giant street party two years ago, when France
beat Brazil 3-0 in the World Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of ecstatic fans, some waving French flags,
instantly crowded onto Paris' most famous avenue to mark the
victory, made possible only by a last-minute goal to tie the game
1-1 and put it into overtime when the French finally came out in
front 2-1.
</P>
<P>
All along the Champs-Elysees, people crowded at apartment
windows and on balconies to watch the show below.
</P>
<P>
"I couldn't watch the game because I was too afraid,"
Stephanie Rey, a 25-year-old Parisian who was wearing a World Cup
t-shirt from 1998, was quoted as saying. "We just walked through
the streets. Now my heart is beating very fast."
</P>
<P>
Jean-Jacques Jemba-Lobe stopped jumping up and down for a
moment to hold up a photograph of his 4-year-old son and grin with
pride.
</P>
<P>
During the game, riot police kept coming over to people with a
radio to listen. When a bus of Welsh children passed through the
Champs, a boy gestured at passersby, asking the score. People
crowded up to the bus to wave and convey the good news: France had
just scored.
</P>
<P>
North of the Arc de Triomphe, a car sped through an
intersection with two Algerian flags sticking out of the window in
honor of French superstar Zinedine Zidane, who is of Algerian
origin. Traffic had been banned on the Champs Elysees itself as a
security precaution.
</P>
<P>
Before the match, most French had confidence that their adored
team, "les Bleus," or the Blues, would come away victorious.
Ninety percent of French people were expecting victory, according
to a poll by the Ifop agency, published in Sunday Le Journal du
Dimanche newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Both French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin attended the match in Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight, I am proud for France and I am proud for the French,
" Chirac said on live television on France's TF1 channel after the
game. "The French team has kept its genius."
</P>
<P>
Jospin called the victory a great "joy" following the World
Cup victory. "This team deserved to win," Jospin said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
