<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lemerre Says His Team's Win on Attacking Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ROTTERDAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Roger Lemerre, coach of France,
said his team's 2-1 triumph over Italy in the Euro 2000 final on
Sunday was a victory for attacking soccer.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a victory for attacking football. I am not going
to hide that," Lemerre said. "We have young players who are
quality players ... I picked them and I am happy that they won the
title for us.
</P>
<P>
"But Italy, offering another kind of football, went very close
to being successful. They also played attacking football."
</P>
<P>
Substitute David Trezeguet clinched the victory with the "
Golden Goal" after the French had scored a dramatic equaliser from
another substitute Sylvain Wiltord just seconds from the end of
normal time.
</P>
<P>
"The miracle happened. We managed to bring it about," Lemerre
said.
</P>
<P>
Italian coach Dino Zoff was philosophical in defeat, saying "I
feel very bad. This is an important event in my life and it's a
defeat," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The French were stronger tonight. We also had quite a lot of
opportunities to score. We lost in extra time but you can't say we
didn't put up a fight."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Italians were the moral champions, the former
Italian goalkeeper said: "It's the reality that counts. Some
matches can go the full 120 minutes and be affected by a small
matter of luck. It's the nature of the game.
</P>
<P>
"It was great that the Italians could put up a fight against
anyone."  
</P>
</TEXT>
