<HEADLINE> Next Five-Year Economic Blueprint Vital for Turkey: Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Develet

Bahceli said on Monday that the eighth five-year development plan "
is vital" for Turkey to display its economic growth potential in
the coming years, Turkey's Anatolia news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Bahceli said at a press briefing that the plan, which was
approved by the parliament last week, aims to reach an average 7
percent economic growth over 2001 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
Through the long-term strategy, Turkey plans to increase its
gross national product to 1.9 trillion dollars by 2023, and thereby
rank among the top ten economies of the world.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey will swiftly put in effect a national program that will
accelerate its membership for the EU," Bahceli said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey's exports are projected to reach 48.8
billion dollars and imports 77.4 billion by 2005 under the plan.
</P>
<P>
He said that the plan gives priorities to structural reforms in
agriculture, social security, public finance management and banking
as well as macro-economic stability, namely, dropping inflation
that will be in chime with the EU criteria.
</P>
<P>
If these policies and reforms foreseen in the plan are carried
out, macro-economic stability, imperative for the long-term
development targets, will be sustained, Bahceli said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country will increase investments in education,
health, technology, infrastructure, energy, irrigation as well as
regional development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
