<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2010GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq on Monday condemned the United States and
Britain for putting on hold 83 health contracts Iraq signed with
foreign countries over the past seven phases of the United Nations
oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
Health Minister Umid Medhat Mubarak said the U.S. and British
delegates at the U.N. Sanctions Committee are continuing the policy
of "fabricating fragile pretexts" to ban Iraq's imports of medicine
and medical appliances. (BC-Iraq-U.S.-Contracts)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli troops are embracing for riots and violence
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the coming weeks surrounding a
Palestinian declaration of statehood, an Israeli newspaper said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Ha'aretz said IDF (Israeli Defense
Forces) is preparing vehicles, helicopters and tanks to confront
possible violent clashes with Palestinians in another popular
uprising, or Intifada.
</P>
<P>
It said the Israeli army has predicted that an imminent
unilateral Palestinian declaration of independence in September may
spark riots in the occupied territories.(BC-Israel-Palestinians-
Violence)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi
said on Monday that Israel should be responsible for the fate of
four Iranian diplomats who were believed to be kidnapped in Lebanon
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Iran holds the "Zionist regime" -- the customary appellation
used by Tehran when referring to Israel -- responsible for the fate
of its missing diplomats, Asefi was quoted by the official Islamic
Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asefi told reporters that Iran has enough evidence that the
diplomats had been transferred to Israel and are still alive in
Israeli jails.(BC-Iran-Israel-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Knesset (parliament) on Monday afternoon
began a first reading debate over a controversial draft bill, which
will enshrine ultra-Orthodox Jews' mass exemption from army
service.
</P>
<P>
The bill, based on recommendations submitted by a special
committee led by retired Supreme Court Justice Tsvi Tal, was
approved by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's cabinet by a vote
of 12 to 2 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed bill, which will need two more readings to become
law, allows those yeshiva (ultra-Orthodox) students to defer their
service until age 23, when they will take a year off from their
religious studies and can be enrolled in universities or work. (BC-
Israel-Jews-Army Service) 
</P>
</TEXT>
