<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Cease-Fire Must Be Multilateral: Attorney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's General Attorney Jaime
Bernal said Monday cease-fire must be multilateral so that in this
way, guerrillas as well as the government understand it's a
question of serious commitment.
</P>
<P>
According to the general attorney, proposals to arrive at an
end to hostilities, in the midst of the country's general
expectation, "must be daring even if they will cause controversy."
</P>
<P>
The attorney's statements came at a time when the government
and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) begin
discussions concerning a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Both parties' statements will be presented at the negotiation
table in San Vicente del Caguan town, in dissension area of
national territory's south.
</P>
<P>
With the debate on a possible accord to cease hostilities, a
new phase of peace talks between the government and the FARC, the
country's most important and oldest guerrilla group, is being
established.
</P>
<P>
The FARC and the government are scheduled to swap proposals
Monday for the first bilateral cease-fire in 16 years in Colombia'
s long-running war.
</P>
<P>
The FARC is likely to make its cease-fire offer hinge on
demands that the government drops a U.S.-backed plan to unleash an
offensive against drug crops and long-standing rebel strongholds
in southern Colombia. rebel sources said. The U.S. Congress last
week agreed to 1.3 billion dollars for mostly military aid to this
war-torn Andean nation.
</P>
<P>
The government proposal will almost certainly include demands
that the FARC not only halts military actions but also "ceases
hostilities" against civilian and suspends kidnappings and
extortion, which together with "taxes" on the drug trade are the
main sources of rebel financing.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks with the FARC were formally launched in January
last year but until now both sides insisted there could be no lull
in the conflict that has cost more than 35,000 lives in the last
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
