<HEADLINE> Schroeder Criticizes U.S. Proposals to Cut Funds for U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
held talks with United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan Monday
in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
In the talks Schroeder criticized indirectly the United States
' proposals to cut its contributions to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that no state had the right to reduce
unilaterally its material support for the U.N.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and the Republican majority in the
U.S. Senate had come to agreement about that the U.S. would cut
its 926 million dollars in back dues to the U.N. on the condition
that the American share of the U.N.'s regular budget be reduced
from 25 percent to 20 percent and peacekeeping budget be dropped
to 25 percent from 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that other U.N. member states must pay more
contributions because of a reduction in U.S. contribution, but he
will not let other states, for example Germany, to bear more
contributions.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said Germany would play a more and more important
role in the affairs in the U.N. and take up more responsibilities
for the U.N. About the permanent seat of the Security Council of
the U.N., Schroeder said that Germany would not act with undue
haste and Germany will consult with partners of the European Union
about it. The strengthening of the United Nations is still one of
the nucleus of the German foreign and security policy and Germany
will also actively participate in the peacekeeping measures of the
U.N., he added.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder told Annan about the opening ceremony of the
International City Construction Conference in which Annan will
take part Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived in Hanover last Saturday to begin his visit to
Germany and he visited the Expo 2000 World Fair there Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In Berlin, Annan met with German President Johannes Rau,
Parliament President Wolfgang Thierse, Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer, former Chancellor Helmut Kohl and other German important
politicians.
</P>
<P>
Annan will end his visit here and leave for Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
