<HEADLINE> Gore Woos U.S. Seniors with Drug Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
Monday courted senior citizens with what he called a "real,
comprehensive" prescription drug plan.
</P>
<P>
"We'll put the power of medical science back in the medicine
cabinets of our mothers and fathers," Gore said in a speech at a
suburban high school in St. Louis, Missouri. "It's the right thing
to do."
</P>
<P>
According to Gore's drug proposal, the government would pay
half of the annual costs up to 5,000 dollars under the Medicare
program. It would extend coverage to 40 million people at a cost
of 255 billion dollars over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
His plan also would limit out-of-pocket costs to consumers to 4,
000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that many senior citizens have to choose between buying
drugs or going without other necessities. "We just should not be
putting our seniors in that position."
</P>
<P>
His plan is in sharp contrast with that of George W. Bush,
presumptive Republican presidential candidate, Gore said, adding
that it would cover far more people than a more modest plan backed
in Congress by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic presidential candidate claimed that his plan is
best because it includes coverage under Medicare, while
Republicans rely on insurance companies to provide the coverage.
</P>
<P>
Gore was accompanied by House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt
during his campaign trip to Missouri.  
</P>
</TEXT>
