<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African President to Attend OAU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- President Thabo Mbeki is to
lead the South African delegation to the 36th summit meeting of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) next week, the Foreign
Affairs Department announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The summit to be held in Lome, Togo, on July 10-12, will also
be a summit of the African Economic Community (AEC), the
department said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be preceded by the 72nd ordinary session of the
OAU/AEC Council of Ministers from July 6-8, which is to be
attended by South African Foreign Affairs Minister Nkosazana
Dlamini-Zuma.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the summit would focus on three main themes:
the challenges of AIDS in Africa; security and stability within
the context of the Algiers Declaration in making 2000 a Year of
Peace and Stability in Africa; regional co-operation and the
integration and the challenge of globalization.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that the summit would focus closely on the
various conflict situations on the continent and the issue of
unconstitutional changes of government, as discussed at the July
1999 summit in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting would discuss progress made since the adoption of
the Sirte Declaration of September 9, 1999, which aimed at
accelerating the implementation of the Abuja Treaty establishing
the African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
"Most significantly, leaders are expected to discuss the draft
Constitutive Act of the African Union and the draft Protocol to
the AEC Treaty relating to the South African Parliament in
accordance with the mandate of the Sirte Declaration," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said South Africa had been actively involved in preparatory
negotiations on the legal texts of the African Union and the
Pan-African Parliament. 
</P>
