<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Presidential Office Rejects Durban Declaration on AIDs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The South African Presidential
Office Monday dismissed the Durban Declaration on AIDS as
something "belonging in the dustbin".
</P>
<P>
The declaration, signed by 5,000 scientists ahead of next
week's international AIDS Conference in Durban, asserts that HIV
is the sole cause of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
It condemns what the scientists regard as revisionist theories
on the cause of AIDS, which they believe has President Thabo
Mbeki's support after he reportedly questioned whether HIV caused
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said, "If the drafters
of the declaration expect to give it to the president, or the
government, it will find its comfortable place among the dustbins
of the office."
</P>
<P>
The declaration was an attempt to divert attention from the
real issues, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
"People can't, under the pretext of meeting in Durban to
discuss questions of HIV/AIDS, circulate a petition all over the
world condemning the president," Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has come under fire in recent months for reportedly
saying that he was not convinced that HIV was the only virus
causing AIDS or death attributed to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has an estimated 4.5 million HIV/AIDS sufferers --
the highest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
