<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
in the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Forest Ministry has finalized a U.N.-
supported project of strategies on forest fire-prevention and
control, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project suggests efforts to develop effective fire reporting
systems, prepare fire management plans, choose tree species which
will drop the financial loss to a minimum, clear off the
combustible forest ground and form fire lanes.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Forest Ministry asked the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) for technical assistance to prevent forest
fires, and to form forest fire management strategies. Three
international and five Turkish advisors completed the project in 22
months.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Minister of Energy and Natural Resources
Cumhur Ersumer briefed here on Monday Sudanese State Minister in
charge of energy Osman Abdalla, on Turkey's experience of energy
development, reported the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Ersumer talked about irrigation, dam construction, hydroelectric
production and build-operate-transfer model used in this field.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministry is ready to extend informative and
technical support to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Energy Ministry will also provide Sudan with the
documentation on the legal arrangement in hydroelectric stations
and irrigation fields of Turkey in a bid to help Sudan implement
its target projects.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- The aggregate oil revenues of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states hit 70 billion U.S. dollars in 1999 against 42
billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The annual economic report for 1999 compiled by the Gulf
Organization for Industrial Consultations indicated that global and
Gulf economic changes, including oil price rise, took place last
year, boosting the general economic performance of the GCC member
states, Al-Hayat reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth rates in Europe and Asia hiked up on the basis
that European and Asian countries are the most important trade
partners of the Gulf countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni Social Development Fund, one of the main
components of social security network, is planning to implement
2700 new projects within four years with the cost of 175 million U.
S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah al-Delaimi, the Chairman of the Fund's Local Societies
Development Unit, was quoted by Al-Hayat as saying that the IBRD
International Development Agency will offer 75 million dollars soft
loans and expecting another sum of 100 million dollars to be
furnished by other donors.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen and Japan signed here on Monday a number of memo
of understandings (MOUs) allowing Yemen to receive a 3.54 million
U.S. dollar-debt-relief grant from Japan.
</P>
<P>
According to Yemeni News Agency, the MOUs which were inked by
Yemeni Planning and Development Minister Ahmad Mohammad Sufan and
Japanese ambassador in Sanaa Akira Hushi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
