<HEADLINE> GCC Welcomes Kuwaiti-Saudi Border Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) on
Monday welcomed a maritime border demarcation accord between Kuwait
and Saudi Arabia, saying it would give impetus to regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here by the General Secretariat of the
six-nation grouping, GCC Secretary-General Jamil Al-Hujailan termed
the signing of the accord as a landmark in the fraternal ties
between the two countries, hoping it would bring to an end the
border disputes between the two Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The deal would also contribute to understanding and stability in
the region and relieve the GCC of a controversial issue among its
members, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Kuwait and Saudi Arabia on Sunday
signed the agreement demarcating a maritime border that runs
through an area rich in oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
The deal was inked on the second day of a three-day state visit
to Kuwait by Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz which
started Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been engaged for several weeks in
bilateral negotiations in a bid to hammer out an agreement on the
offshore zone where the al-Dorah oilfield is located. The oilfield
is claimed by Iran, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, which demarcated their land borders two

years ago, met in the Saudi capital in early June for talks on
their
maritime border but did not reach an agreement at that stage.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the al-Dorah oilfield resurfaced in May when
Riyadh and Kuwait City protested against Iran's drillings in the
field. Tehran, which also claims the area, suspended the activities
later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
