<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Declare July 8 "National Day Against Violence" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Students of Tehran University have
decided to observe July 8 as the "National Day Against Violence" to
mark the tragic student dormitory incident last year, the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
On July 8, 1999, anti-riot police raided a Tehran University
dormitory to crack down on student protests against the closure of
the outspoken Persian daily Salam by the conservative authorities.
</P>
<P>
The incident sparked six days of bloody riots in Tehran and
other cities, believed to be the worst of its kind since the 1979
Islamic revolution. Several people were injured in the riots, which
also led to the trial of some police officers.
</P>
<P>
According to the IRNA report, Tehran University students will
offer flowers to the people in the main squares of Tehran on July 8
to mark the anniversary of the police crackdown on students last
year.
</P>
<P>
"We will offer flowers to the people with a smile" to mark the
anniversary of the incident and "will avoid any action which may
lead to violence," a student organization called "the Office to
Foster Unity" told the agency.
</P>
<P>
The organization added it has decided to hold peaceful events to
denounce violence that was used against the students last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
