<HEADLINE> Irish PM Hails N.Ireland Peacemaker George Mitchell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
paid tribute Monday to former United States senator George
Mitchell for his role in trying to bring peace to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the presentation of the Tipperary International
Peace Award to Mitchell, held in Tipperary, southern Ireland,
Ahern hailed Mitchell's efforts to build trust among the rival
parties in Northern Ireland, a Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the people of Ireland, I would like to thank
George Mitchell once again for his enormous contribution to peace,
an achievement of which both he and President (Bill) Clinton can
be truly proud," the report quoted Ahern as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone who took part in the talks acquired huge respect for
George Mitchell, who encouraged everyone to contribute but who was
also determined to build brick by brick a consensus that would
result in agreement," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by Clinton, retired U.S. Senator Mitchell played a
key role in bringing peace to Northern Ireland, helping broker the
landmark 1998 peace agreement that paved the way for a home rule
government including rival Catholic and Protestant parties.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, Mitchell said he was optimistic a lasting peace
could be achieved in the province of Northern Ireland. But he also
warned it would be a long haul.
</P>
<P>
"I commend all participants for their perseverance. But there
will be setbacks and no one should think it will be free of
difficulty. But there is a feeling of hope, of optimism, of
accomplishment now the Northern Ireland government is up and
running," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's easy to rebuild a building destroyed in a conflict but
to change hearts and minds is the most difficult thing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell's patient, no-nonsense approach was widely credited
as a key factor in keeping rival parties at the negotiating table
and taking the gun out of Irish politics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
