<HEADLINE> Another 1,000 Eritreans Repatriated From Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Another 1,000 Eritreans and
Ethiopians of Eritrean origin were repatriated from Ethiopia
Sunday, said the Eritrean Foreign Affairs Ministry in a statement
available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The statement claimed that the "recent deportees were
arbitrarily taken from their homes in Ethiopia and sent to the
border where they arrived in the town of Shambuko."
</P>
<P>
"Neither the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC)
and the State of Eritrea was informed in advance," it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the Eritrean government has worked in
 coordination with the ICRC to repatriate voluntarily Ethiopians
residing in Eritrean, saying the Ethiopian government refuses to
accord similar cooperation and respect for the rights of Eritrean
residents.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC-sponsored voluntary repatriation which began in June
this year has resulted in the safe return of 8,000 Ethiopians to
their home country.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, 150 Eritreans were forced out of their homes
and repatriated from Ethiopia. So far, a total of 71,449
Eritreans have been repatriated from Ethiopia since the beginning
of the conflict between the two countries about two years ago,
the statement said. 
</P>
