<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Begins Debate on Controversial Draft Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset (parliament) on
Monday afternoon began a first reading debate over a controversial
draft bill, which will enshrine ultra-Orthodox Jews' mass exemption

from army service.
</P>
<P>
The bill, based on recommendations submitted by a special
committee led by retired Supreme Court Justice Tsvi Tal, was
approved by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's cabinet by a vote
of 12 to 2 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed bill, which will need two more readings to become
law, allows those yeshiva (ultra-Orthodox) students to defer their
service until age 23, when they will take a year off from their
religious studies and can be enrolled in universities or work.
</P>
<P>
After the "year of decision", they could choose to stay in
yeshiva to keep studying Torah (Jewish Bible) or join Israel
Defense Forces (IDF) for a relatively short period and then enter
the workforce.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the IDF traditionally granted these Jewish students'

exemption from service, but they were also forbidden to work.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Israel's Supreme Court ruled that the present deferral
system is illegal and urged the government to pass legislation to
solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Before Monday's debate, Barak told Israel Radio that there is a
need to develop a gradual system to deal with the issue and prevent
a serious rift in the Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
The bill will allow much more religious students, even tens of
thousands, to defend the Jewish state without violating their ways
of lives, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister's remarks invited severe criticism
from secular Israelis, who argued that the bill only legalize the
current discriminatory system.
</P>
<P>
They also blamed Barak for backing up from his election promises
again under the pressure of ultra-Orthodox parties, whom Barak
dares
not to irritate at the current stage to smooth his efforts to push
forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that in last year's general election, Barak won
many secular votes with a "One Nation, One IDF recruitment" slogan
and Barak's deeds today just betrayed these voters.
</P>
<P>
Several Israeli soldiers had set up a protest tent outside
Barak's office in Jerusalem for their hunger strike against the
bill.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic scene reveals the widening gap between the
ultra-Orthodox Jews, who did not work or join the army and depend
their daily lives upon government funds, and the secular Jews, who
work, pay taxes, and guard the state in the IDF.
</P>
<P>
The secular claim that the ultra-Orthodox are just parasites and

urged them to share the responsibility to build and defend their
country, while the ultra-Orthodox insist their Torah studying are
essential for the continued existence of the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that with the support of ultra-Orthodox parties,
the bill will win a 61 majority in the 120-member Knesset and pass
its first reading later Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Prince Winds up Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz on Monday left here for home after paying a three-day
state visit to Kuwait, during which the two countries signed a
maritime border demarcation accord.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed here by Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sabah
Al-Jaber Al-Sabah and his Saudi counterpart Saud Al-Faisal on
Sunday. Emir of Kuwait Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah and Abdullah,
also Saudi First Deputy Prime Minister, presided over the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The deal was designed to settle any border disputes between
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait over their land boundaries, demarcated
about 80 years ago, and the sea lines including the Persian Gulf-
located al-Dorah oilfield which is disputed between Kuwait and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Local dailies on Monday quoted high-ranking sources as saying
that the new Saudi-Kuwaiti sea lines lie one nautical mile deep,
south of the Gulf island of Um-almurdam, instead of the previous 3-
mile-deep offshore lines.
</P>
<P>
The deal also involved demarcating the joint coast and common
sharing of the natural resources in the area.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the Gulf islands of Karuh and Um-almurdam were
Kuwaiti territories, the sources said, adding that the island of
Felka became completely a Kuwaiti land.
</P>
<P>
On the importance of the agreement, Kuwaiti Assistant Foreign
Minister Khalid al-Garallah told local daily Al-Kabas that the
milestone deal serves the interests of the two peoples, and has "
paved the way for trilateral Kuwaiti, Saudi and Iranian border
negotiations in the near future."
</P>
<P>
Abdullah held talks on Saturday with Kuwait Emir Sheikh Jaber on
the ways of developing bilateral relations, and on the regional and
international issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
