<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Raise Water Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Knesset (Parliament)
Finance Committee has approved a 15-percent hike in water prices
for agriculture to be implemented within two years as an emergency
water-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
An Israel Radio report said on Monday Israeli farmers will
receive an immediate advance comprehensive payment of 80 million
shekels (20 million U.S. dollars) for enabling the increase
proposal to be endorsed.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Israeli Water Council is meeting Monday
afternoon to discuss other emergency measures, including
restrictions on watering gardens and washing cars.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Environment Dalia Itzik is opposed to the call,
saying she will not back any measure that will turn Israel and its
nature reserves into a dry and yellow landscape.
</P>
<P>
The council is also discussing further cuts on water for
agricultural use.
</P>
<P>
Water for agriculture has already been cut by 40 percent, but
according to the recommendations being discussed, the cuts will be
raised to 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
The proposal has met strong opposition from the country's
farmers.
</P>
<P>
A serious water shortage facing Israel has sent the related
departments in the country into quick actions. The government
dispatched a high-level "emergency panel" of water experts and
government officials to Turkey in June to examine water sources and
discuss possible timetables for importing water.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is expected to return to Turkey this week to
conclude negotiations on supplying fresh water to Israel amid
concerns about a high price proposed by Turkish authorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Minister of National Infrastructure Eli
Suissa has also been formulating proposals to be submitted to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak by the end of July for saving water and
creating new water resources.
</P>
<P>
Experts here view importing fresh water only as an emergency
measure and set the long-term goal on setting up desalination
plants to create sustained water resources.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli infrastructure and environment ministers, together
with the water commissioner, are scheduled to visit a desalination
plant in the southern port city of Eilat next week in an effort to
coordinate the interior ministerial program to build desalination
plants along the coast.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli national water company, Mekorot, warned in June that
by fall, Israel's three central reservoirs will reach "
unprecedented low levels," highlighting the country's water crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
