<HEADLINE> Egypt to Move Precious Antiquities to Safer Museums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The remains of Napoleon's fleet and
other treasures will be moved to safer museums within Egypt after a
burglary revealed their current location is not secure, a senior
antiquities official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gaballah Ali Gaballah, secretary general of the Supreme Council
of Antiquities, told the official Middle East News Agency that the
vestiges of the French fleet sunk by Britain's Lord Nelson in the
1798 Battle of the Nile will be moved a short distance away from
the Qayt Bey Museum to the National Maritime Museum in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Pistols, candle-holders and other items belonging to the periods
ruled by the Ottomans, Fatimids, Mamelukes, and the Mohammed Ali
dynasty will be transferred from Qayt Bey to the Islamic Museum in
Cairo, Gaballah said.
</P>
<P>
However, tourists will still be able to visit the old Qayt Bey
fortress.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's decision came Monday following the theft of 500-year-old
coins minted under Sultan Ashraf Qayt Bey, who ruled from 1468 to
1498, from the museum.
</P>
<P>
The fortress also stands on the site of the ancient lighthouse
of Alexandria, one of the seven wonders of the ancient world.
</P>
</TEXT>
