<HEADLINE> Egyptian Authorities Arrest Four Colleagues of Detained Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian state security
prosecution ordered Monday the arrest of four colleagues of an
Egyptian-American sociology professor who was detained at the
weekend on charges of trying to undermine the country's stability.
</P>
<P>
The state prosecutor's office said the four detainees were
members of the Ibn Khaldoun Center for Development Studies, a non-
government organization (NGO), headed by the professor, Saad Eddin
Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim, an Egyptian-born U.S. citizen who also worked at the
American University in Cairo, was arrested early Saturday. He was
accused of receiving money from abroad without prior permission of
the authorities and writing articles and producing films to tarnish
Egypt's image.
</P>
<P>
Under Egyptian laws, NGOs must get permission from government
agencies in advance for receiving funds from foreign parties.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor's office said arrest warrants were also issued
for four other members of the center. It did not say what the eight
were being charged with.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's emergency law stipulates that suspects can be detained
without charge for two weeks, which can be renewed indefinitely.
</P>
