<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Economy Vulnerable to Potential Shocks: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Among others, a sharp swing in major exchange rates is possible,
when trade imbalances of the major countries become a matter of
concern in financial markets, they said in the World Economic and
Social Survey 2000, released in New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
They worry about an "excessively" restrictive monetary stance
by developed nations as almost all of them are simultaneously
tightening monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
They forecast that a large and sustained drop in assets prices
in major economies especially in the United States may reduce
consumption and investment and send the world economy "to a much
lower rate of growth."
</P>
<P>
The survey said oil prices could remain above 30 U.S. dollars
per barrel for a sustained period, which could prompt further
increases in interest rates in developed economies and slow growth
in these countries and the rest of the world. 
</P>
