<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Onlooking of Tragic Blast in Chechnya's Argun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Itar-Tass news agency late
Monday reported some spot details of the smashing blast in the
Chechen city of Argun, the most serious one of a series of
terrorist explosions staged by rebels Sunday night, naming it a
shocking tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The event occurred at about 20:00 Moscow time (1700 GMT) Sunday
evening, when scores of Russian policemen were resting after their
supper in their rooms of a military dormitory in the city of Argun,
10 kilometers to the southeast of the republic's capital Grozny. A
heavy "Ural" truck rammed at a high speed suddenly into the gate
of the police hostel and then a powerful explosion went off
immediately, Tass cited witnesses as saying.
</P>
<P>
Directly after the blast, motor and gunfire were opened at the
building, where an OMON (special police) unit from the region of
Chelyabinsk and a Chechen riot police group were stationed, the
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary reports by the Russian side, the truck
was carrying about 500 kilograms of explosives, most likely a
mixture of TNT and plastic dynamites. The blast left a hole in the
ground five meters deep and ten meters wide. Parts of the vehicle
were hurled hundreds of meters from the epicenter. The driver was
killed on the spot, and the police building was fully ruined and
civilian houses nearby were badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
Tass quoted the Russian Interior Ministry's interior agency in
the troubled republic as saying that at least 31 men died and
dozens were wounded in the hostel explosion.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers have recovered 26 bodies from the rubble of the police
dormitory by Monday afternoon, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The blast in Argun also killed three civilians who were staying
near the building. Now ruins-clearing work is still underway and
more corpses are expected to be found. Federal forces have begun
combing the city and its environs, it said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that the truck stuffed with explosives was being
operated by two kamikaze drivers. The vehicle managed to approach
the dormitory because it was already in town beforehand and did
not have to pass any checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
Russian presidential aide on Chechnya Sergei Yastrzhembsky told
the press Monday that Argun saw the worst one of all the attacks
overnight due to "no sufficient cordons around the military
buildings."
</P>
<P>
"There was only one Kamaz truck at the entry to the premises,
and there was no concrete wall. The police opened fire for effect
at the Ural truck approaching the dormitory, and the vehicle
exploded. The explosion left a huge crater behind and ruined two
buildings located 40 and 15 meters away," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is no complete information as to the death toll available
so far. Rescue work continues, and the picture may become clear by
the end of the day, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Sunday night's bomb attack in Argun was followed by several
hours of fighting, as "Chechen rebels were attempting to seize the
federal commandant's building," said a representative of the
Russia's Argun military commandant's office, cited by Interfax.
</P>
</TEXT>
