<HEADLINE> Clerides Criticizes Turkish Troops Movement in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
Monday slashed Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash for the
movement by the Turkish occupation forces to the demilitarized
zone in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his talks with Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis in Athens, Clerides said that the measures taken by
Denktash concerning the peace-keeping force led him to a
confrontation with the U.N. Security Council because it had
decided to extend the presence of the U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in
Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader blocked this force that had the
authority by the U.N. Security Council to act on the basis of
avoiding tensions, Clerides said, adding that the Turkish side
would not be able to maintain those measures for a long time.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Simitis said that the Turkish side confirmed its
intransigence and defiance of all the existing agreements and U.N.
decisions.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side decided to change the status quo in the
region which existed since the cease-fire agreement, Simitis said,
stressing that the Greek side condemned this action and would take
all necessary measures to underline the need for the restoration
of the status quo in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas Monday
described the movement by Turkish forces in Cyprus as "illegal and
unacceptable," saying that it was a trick by Denktash in an
attempt to shift the interest of the international public opinion
away from the essence of the talks on Cyprus that is to be held in
Geneva on July 5.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that the U.N. must ask Denktash to comply
not only with older agreements but to be consistent with the
commitment he had undertaken to settle the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974, when Turkish troops
invaded and occupied the northern third of the eastern
Mediterranean island after a Greek Cypriot coup in Nicosia
instigated by Greece's military rulers.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between Clerides
and Denktash have already been held in New York and Geneva
respectively to prepare the ground for substantive negotiations
leading to a comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, along with Greece, has insisted that the island should
be reunited in a federation formula in line with the U.N.
resolutions while northern Cyprus and Turkey demand that a
confederation formed by two sovereign states be set up on the
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
