<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac said
Monday that the European Union (EU) sanctions against Austria will
stay in force until the three experts designated by the European
Court of Human Rights submit their report on the situation of
refugees, immigrants and minority groups in Austria.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also denied that the EU has fixed a date for the three
experts to submit their report, as was indicated last week by
Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel, who said that the report
should be submitted in September.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have a time to fix. It is up to them (experts) to take
the necessary time as was very clearly indicated by Portugal (
former EU presidency state). From now till then, the bilateral
measures of the 14 (EU states) remain in force," said Chirac at a
press conference on the first working day of the French EU
presidency which started on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The 14 other EU states imposed sanctions upon Austria after a
coalition government including the far-right Freedom Party came to
power in January.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include a suspension of bilateral cooperation,
refusal to support Austria's candidacy for international posts,
and minimum relations with Austrian ambassadors. 
