<HEADLINE> Endangered Penguins Released into Sea in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 penguins
evacuated from Dassen and Robben islands had been released into
the sea at Cape Recife near Port Elizabeth by Monday noon.
</P>
<P>
Oil spill from the bulk oil carrier, Treasure, has endangered
tens of thousands of penguins on Dassen and Robben islands since
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The penguin colony at Dassen Island was fenced to protect the
birds venturing into the oil polluted sea.
</P>
<P>
The chief marine and coastal conservation inspector in Port
Elizabeth Harry Watts said another batch of some 900 penguins were
expected in Port Elizabeth later on Monday night for release.
</P>
<P>
He said the birds were being transported to Port Elizabeth in
trucks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South African National Foundation for the
Conservation of Coastal Birds (SANFCCB) has appealed for more
volunteers to help clean more than 20,000 oil covered penguins.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday Deputy Minister of Environmental Affairs and
Tourism Rejoice Mabudhafasi inspected facilities at the SANFCCB
centre, while Cape Metropolitan Council mayor William Bantom
presented a cheque for 50,000 rand (7,300 U.S. dollars) to ease
the financial burden at SANFCCOB.
</P>
<P>
South African Maritime Safety Authority (Samsa) spokesman
Captain Bill Dernier said on Monday afternoon that unseasonable
weather patterns, while helping the collection of penguins as well
as the oil recovery operation at the wreck, continued to keep the
oil slicks at sea. 
</P>
