<HEADLINE> S. African AIDS Panel Urged to Help Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Health Minister
Manto Tshabalala-Msimang Monday urged the Presidential AIDS
Advisory Panel to focus on assisting the government to save lives.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the panel's scientists and observers on its final
round of meetings, Tshabalala-Msimang asked the panellists to pay
particular attention to identifying the shortcomings of current
HIV/AIDS programs and advise the government on what prevention
strategies it should take.
</P>
<P>
She said they should study the role that poverty plays in
spreading the disease.
</P>
<P>
She said a more reliable and accurate surveillance system had
to be developed after the United Nations AIDS report raised
concerns that projections based on antenatal surveys may not be
reliable.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the "Durban Declaration", signed by 5,000
scientists refuting what they regard as "revisionist" theories on
the cause of AIDS, she said the government respected the
panellists' right to support a particular point of view.
</P>
<P>
She said the declaration was not directly linked to the AIDS
conference to be held in Durban next week.
</P>
<P>
The declaration should be viewed as an independent document
supported by independent scientists, who do not necessarily
represent the AIDS conference, Tshabalala-Msimang said.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus has always been to provide a platform for open
constructive dialog so that we can learn and get ideas on how to
comprehensively respond to the challenge we face," she said.
</P>
<P>
Tshabalala-Msimang said the government would not be deterred
from capturing ideas from anyone if it would "enable us to better
serve our people".
</P>
<P>
The panel, set up by President Thabo Mbeki earlier this year to
advise the government on how to fight the disease, comprises more
than 30 scientists who are evenly split between experts
questioning the link between HIV and AIDS and those subscribing
to the conventional view that the HIV causes AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
