<P>
According to the minister who attended the meeting held last
weekend in Lusaka, the 17th session of the Angolan-Zambian Joint
Commission of Defense and Security has created a mechanism for
treating, through dialog and constructive forms, possible
incidents or incomprehension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Fernando da Piedade said that the principle of common control
of the frontier was adopted by the two sides and both countries
agreed to prevent unsteady actions from happening.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to establish a communication system to improve
contacts and opinion exchange between the regional commanders and
other security officers in the eastern Angolan provinces and the
western Zambian areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the joint commission also decided to set up a
technical committee to investigate previous incidents and inform
their respective governments as soon as conclusive findings are
compiled, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Angola and Zambia have been strained during
the Angolan civil war. The Angolan government has accused the
Zambian government of giving logistic support to the Angolan
rebels led by Jonas Savimbi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
