<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold Bipartisan Talks on Executive Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan ruling People's
Alliance (PA) and the main opposition United National Party (UNP)
will meet later this week to decide if the Executive Presidency
should continue, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
They said a joint delegation of the PA led by President
Chandrika Kumaratunga and the UNP headed by Ranil Wickremesinghe
will meet on Friday on the issue as a part of the bipartisan talks
on the constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga, who rode to power in 1994 promising the abolition
of Presidency, failed to do so after her draft constitutional
reform proposals, changing among others the Executive Presidency
to Westminster Democracy, stuck in Parliament for want of two-
thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
The proposed reforms advocated abolition of Presidency and
offered a package of devolution proposals to grant autonomy to the
provinces, especially to the Tamil-dominated north and east as
political solution to end the long-running ethnic civil war with
the separatist Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
More recently, the government came up with a new transitional
provisions which included retention of the Presidency for a
further six years as Kumaratunga was reelected for the second term
last December.
</P>
<P>
The UNP, which had introduced the Executive Presidency in the
island 22 years ago, are hoping to abolish the office which lends
excessive powers to the head of state.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, committee members of both the PA and UNP will meet
Wednesday to discuss the proposed new constitutional reforms on
finance, law and national security. The conclusions of this
meeting will be handed over to the president and the opposition
leader on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan talks on constitutional reform have made
significant progress during the past month as the two sides have
reached agreement on several matters, including an interim council
to administer the war-torn north and east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
