<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Chief Executive Starts Dialogue With Politicians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's military ruler General
Pervez Musharraf Monday started meetings with the country's key
political leaders in a move to bridge the gulf between the
government and the political parties.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive on Monday met Raja Zafar ul Haq, acting
chief of Pakistan Muslim League (PML) whose leader is the ousted
prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, who is now in prison. This is
Musharraf's first meeting with a PML leader since the military
coup in October last year.
</P>
<P>
"We will look into the chief executive's proposals for
amendment in the constitution and revival of democracy," Haq told
reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf said last month that he will begin meetings
with what he called "clean politicians" in July.
</P>
<P>
Haq said that his meeting with Musharraf, which lasted for over
two hours, discussed the country's political and economic
situation and other vital national matters.
</P>
<P>
PML sources said cases against Nawaz Sharif figured in the
meeting. General Musharraf reportedly told the PML that the cases
are in the courts and the government respects the judiciary
independence.
</P>
<P>
Sharif has been sentenced to life imprisonment in a hijacking
case, is being tried in a corruption case and also is also charged
with treason.
</P>
<P>
Haq said he will inform the former prime minister of the
meeting. "Our meeting mainly concerned the revival of democracy.
Of course, I cannot tell all."
</P>
<P>
"Politicians associated with various national political parties
visited the chief executive's office in Islamabad on Monday where
they held separate one-to-one meetings" with General Musharraf,
said an official statement.
</P>
<P>
Those politicians were apprised on the government's reform
agenda, the statement said. It described the atmosphere of talks
as "free, candid and cordial."
</P>
<P>
Among the politicians whom General Musharraf met Monday were
also Maulana Fazlur Rehman, Chief of Islamic group "Jamiat Ulema-e-
Islam," and Miaz Mohammad Azhar, a PML dissident and former
governor of Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
Terming Musharraf's meetings with the politicians as a good
start, Pakistan's Interior Minister Moinuddin Haider Monday said
the process will continue.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good start and the meeting process will continue,"
Haider told a press briefing here. He said the meetings are part
of the government's effort to let others join the reform process.
</P>
<P>
"Reform is not alone the responsibility of the government. It
is a collective responsibility. We want others to join this
process and the meetings are part of it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
