<HEADLINE> No Sino-Pak Cooperation in Missile Technology: Pak FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Abdul
Sattar Monday refuted U.S. media reports about cooperation between
Pakistan and China to build long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
"There is no such cooperation," Sattar told a news conference
here.
</P>
<P>
New York Times on Sunday reported that the American
intelligence agencies have told the Clinton administration and
Congress that China has continued to aid Pakistan's effort to
build long-range missiles that could carry nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Sattar said Pakistan had received limited help from China about
short-range missile technology in 1993, which did not violate the
Missile Technology Control Regime (MTCR) criteria, to which China
was committed.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Pakistan has not received anything
from China which is inconsistent with Beijing's commitment to the
MTCR.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan's program is sufficiently advanced, so we can
continue research ourselves," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
