<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Economy to Grow 3.5 Percent in 2000: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The upswing is subject to various short-term threats and growth
in most of the poorest countries remains inadequate to meeting
world poverty-fighting goals, said the U.N. World Economic and
Social Survey 2000.
</P>
<P>
Continued strength is expected in North America and improvement
in most other parts of the world, especially South and East Asia,
Latin America and Europe, said the report, adding that the
economies of China and India, which have been growing at 7 or 6
percent in recent years, are expected to continue at a similar
pace at least through 2001.
</P>
<P>
The report said recent developments in the Baltic countries,
Central and Eastern Europe and the Commonwealth of Independent
States have also been positive. Growth for the entire region is
expected to reach 3.75 percent in 2000, up from 2.1 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Output in Africa is forecast to increase by 4.25 percent in
2000, but the growth rate is unevenly spread, with output per
person falling this year in six countries in Sub-Saharan Africa,
and in at least 14 of the world's 48 least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"In many ways, the international economy is resuming its pre-
crisis mode," the report claimed. Capital flows to emerging
economies are rising again and international prices of most
commodities have bottomed out, with world trade volume expected to
grow by about 8 percent this year, up from less than 5 percent in
1999 and about 3 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
