<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Rounds Up 300 Rebel Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan police and army have
rounded up 300 persons in the northwestern part of the country who
are suspected to be Tamil Tiger rebels, the state radio said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the 300 persons were detained on Sunday during a
joint search and cordon operation in the Puttalam district, some
140 kilometers north of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted police sources as saying that 160 of those
detained were released after interrogation and that at least five
of those still in detention are senior members of Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The surprise raid was ordered by Mahinda Balasuriya, Deputy
Inspector General of Police for the North Western Province, who
believed the rebels are using Puttalam as "a hideout for terrorist
activity."
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting for a separate homeland
called Eelam for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east
since 1983. More than 60,000 people have been killed in the
conflict. 
</P>
