<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 68,000 Displaced Angolans Face Terrible Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 68,000 war-displaced Angolans
sheltered in the central South Kwanza province are facing
"terrible conditions", an official of the ministry of the
assistance and social reintegration said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Bernardo Martins, Gabela, a city 270 kilometers
southeast of Luanda, has lodged most of the refugees who are in
dire need of all subsistence.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, most of them from the districts of Ebo, Quibala,
Waku Kungo and Mussende, faced shortages of food, clothing,
medicine, tents and other implements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The military situation in the South Kwanza province has in
recent months been unstable, especially in the districts of
Quibala, Ebo and Waku Kungo. In addition, the northeastern
district of Mussende is occupied by the rebels of the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Dozens of refugees flow from the UNITA-controlled areas into
Gabela every day, Martins said. He urged the aid organizations to
send assistance because the existing stocks are not enough to
sustain the needy.
</P>
<P>
The total number of war refugees in South Kwanza province is
estimated at 150,000, most of them women, children and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are taking steps to remedy the situation, Martins
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
