<HEADLINE> UAE Hails Saudi-Kuwaiti Maritime Border Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The recently-signed maritime
border demarcation pact between Saudi Arabia and Kuwait scored a
new victory for the citizens of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC),
said a senior official of the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The agreement proved that there are always peaceful options that
stand to be better alternatives to escalation of border disputes
all over the world, said UAE Deputy Prime Minister Sultan Bin Zayed
al-Nahyan in a statement issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It once again proves that historical bonds are the shortest way
to resolve any issue," said the minister in the statement issued by
the Zayed Center for Coordination and Follow Up (ZCCF), which he
also serves as chairman.
</P>
<P>
Sultan also expressed his country's hope that other Arab
countries, which are involved in border disputes, will follow the
example of Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia inked on Sunday the pact for the
demarcation of their sea borders, a step which is bound to pave the
way for both sides to seek agreement with Iran on settlement of
border
disputes in northern Gulf, found to be rich in oil and gas
reserves.  There is a long-time dispute between the UAE and Iran
over the three Gulf islands of Greater and Lesser Tunbs and Abu
Musa.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has called on Iran to settle the issue through either
negotiations or referral to the International Court of Justice in
the Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The three islands, located near the strategic shipping lanes in
the Gulf, are claimed by both the UAE and Iran, but occupied by the
latter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
