<HEADLINE> UAE's Currency to Peg Stably to U.S. Dollar: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)'s
currency, dirham, pegged to the U.S. dollar, is expected to remain
stable over the next two years due to expected higher oil revenues
and an upturn in foreign reserves and assets, economists said.
</P>
<P>
The strength of the dollar will ensure the strength of the
dirham against other main currencies, said the Economist
Intelligence Unit (EIU), an information provider for companies
establishing and managing operations across national borders, in
its latest report on UAE released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The currency will continue to be pegged to the U.S. dollar at a
rate of 3.67 dirhams. The strength of UAE's foreign reserves and
international investments serve as a guarantee of the stability of
the dirham, a position that will be boosted by strength of oil
prices over the forecast period," said the 50-year-old London-based
global information provider in its report.
</P>
<P>
"This is significant for the UAE, as the goods which it re-
exports, mainly imports, are dominated in yen," noted the report.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, the domestic interest rates will continue to track
U.S. rates and are thus projected to rise in 2000, as U.S. three-
month rates hit 6.3 percent, before slipping back in 2001 in line
with U.S. rates of 6.1 percent," it added.
</P>
<P>
"Higher oil revenue will find its way into greater government
spending by individual emirates, which in turn will enhance private
sector confidence, investment and general activity," said the
report.
</P>
<P>
"The benefit of higher oil prices to neighboring oil producers
will also provide a boost to UAE's re-export trade, particularly
with Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Iran," added the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
