<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Condemns Adoption of Sharia in Northern States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has condemned
the adoption of Islamic Sharia law in some northern states in
Nigeria as a politically oriented move to derail democracy,
Nigerian press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time when the government made its stand
clear on the issue after Kano became the fourth northern state to
introduce the controversial law last month after Zamfara, Niger
and Sokoto.
</P>
<P>
"We know very well that the real religious leaders are not the
ones promoting this, therefore it is a political strategy to
derail this administration, divert attention and move on to where
we don't want to go," Nigeria's Information Minister Jerry Gana
was quoted as saying in the capital Abuja on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the agreement reached between the
federal government and governors of the 19 northern states to
suspend the implementation of Sharia and return to the existing
penal code still remains valid.
</P>
<P>
"The decision of the Council of States requesting all the
governors to revert to the penal code in implementing the aspects
of Sharia is still the guiding decision," he said, stressing "that
is the one the Federal Government is still upholding and
respecting."
</P>
<P>
"The Federal Government is absolutely in control of the
controversy generated by Sharia and we know that if we do not act
wisely, the way we are doing now, we would have played ourselves
into the trap that have been set by those who are promoting this
issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to fall into that trap, so we shall just move
on with the issues of development, progress and stability of
Nigeria," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
