<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Amend Trust Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The draft amendment of China's
Trust Law was submitted to the 16th session of the Standing
Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), the
country's top law-making body, here today for examination and
approval.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, the draft was presented to the 23rd conference
of the Standing Committee of the Eighth NPC for primary
examination, and later major revisions were made to the draft.
</P>
<P>
In a presentation on the revision to the Chinese legislators,
Zhang Xuwu, vice-chairman of the NPC's Law Committee, said that
since the reform of the trust industry is still going on and the
status of trust companies is still uncertain, the conditions for
regulating the trust system are not ripe.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the draft only stipulates the basic
relations between trustors and trustees, and has crossed out the
parts related to trust investment companies.
</P>
<P>
The draft has revisions on the rights and duties of trustees
and trustors, covering over 30 articles, mainly as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- The precondition for establishing trusteeship is that the
property in trust is the legitimate property of the trustor, and
trusteeship based on demanding repayment of loans is legally
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
-- Property in trust does not belong to the category of estate
or clearing property when the trustor or trustee is dead,
bankrupted or dissolved. Property in trust is not allowed to be
disposed of except as stipulated by law.
</P>
<P>
-- Quite a few revisions and supplements have been made
concerning the rights and duties of the trustee, the trustor and
the beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
-- To promote the development of public welfare undertakings,
the draft stipulates that the trusting of public welfare property
shall be approved by the administrative authorities of public
welfare undertakings instead of the regulatory authorities of the
trust industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also noted that further revisions will be made to the
draft after in-depth investigation and examination.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft Amendment Product Quality Law to Boost Consumers' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The latest draft amendment to the
Product Quality Law stipulates that consumers have the right to
know the facts about the quality of products. It also specifies
legal measures against making and selling fake products.
</P>
<P>
The draft amendment was submitted to the Standing Committee of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top
legislature, today for examination and approval.
</P>
<P>
In a presentation on the draft to the 16th session of the NPC
Standing Committee, Qiao Xiaoyang, vice-chairman of the NPC's Law
Committee, said that the draft basically meets the needs of legal
supervision of product quality, following two sessions of
examination and revision.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that some legislators propose that the producer
indicate clearly in the specifications of the product such items
as production time, sell-by date, ingredients, grade and safety
specifications, so as to let customers know the facts about the
quality of the product.
</P>
<P>
To curb the rampant production and selling of fake products
across the country, the draft stipulates that fines and criminal
charges will be resorted to in fighting against such activities.
</P>
<P>
The draft also stipulates that the quality supervision and
inspection authorities are not allowed to participate in the
making or selling of any kind of product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Revise Fisheries Law for Better Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee is considering revising the existing fisheries
law by introducing fishing licenses and production ceilings into
the fish stocks protection mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang, elaborated on the draft
revisions to the fisheries law to the Ninth NPC Standing Committee
at its 16th meeting, which opened today.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many problems have sprung up in the fishing
industry, said Chen, who said that lots of aquatic farms have been
encroached upon, excessive fishing has endangered fish resources,
and some offenders might have escaped punishment.
</P>
<P>
The draft revisions stipulate that local governments above the
county level should strengthen their protection of important
aquatic production farms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state will set quotas for licensed fishermen.
</P>
<P>
The draft also recommends that the state cultivate new aquatic
breeds and spread them with the approval from the state.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that the draft revisions stipulate businesses or
individuals who damage the aquatic environment, pollute water or
foreigners fishing illegally in areas of water administered by the
Chinese government, should be punished in accordance with law.
</P>
<P>
Effective on July 1, 1986, the present fisheries law has helped
to safeguard fishing resources and meet the commercial demand for
fish.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, China has had the largest fisheries industry in the
world. In 1999, the volume of China's aquatic products reached 41.
22 million tons, valued at 252.4 billion yuan (about 30.4 billion
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Puts New Meteorological Satellite in Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Fengyun 2 meteorological
satellite, launched June 25 by means of a Long March 3 carrier
rocket from the Xichang Satellite Launch Center in southwest China
's Sichuan Province, was successfully positioned in a
geostationary orbit at 21:28 (Beijing time) today.
</P>
<P>
The positioning was monitored and controlled by the Xi'an
Satellite Measuring and Monitoring Center in Xi'an, the provincial
capital of northwestern Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
The Fengyun 2, the second of its kind launched by China, can
provide meteorological information and monitor X-rays from the Sun
as well as the radiation of space particles.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, with a designed working life of three years,
will be transferred to the China Meteorological Administration
after a period of in-orbit tests.
</P>
<P>
The satellite was jointly developed by the Shanghai Aerospace
Technology Research Institute under the China Aerospace
Corporation, the Chinese Research Institute of Space Technology
and several other research institutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
