<HEADLINE> Iran Holds Israel Responsible for Missing Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi said on Monday that Israel should be responsible
for the fate of four Iranian diplomats who were believed to be
kidnapped in Lebanon in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Iran holds the "Zionist regime" -- the customary appellation
used by Tehran when referring to Israel -- responsible for the fate
of its missing diplomats, Asefi was quoted by the official Islamic
Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asefi told reporters that Iran has enough evidence that the
diplomats had been transferred to Israel and are still alive in
Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
He added that during the past 18 years since the event, Israel
has been trying to distract international attention from the
kidnapping which is in violation of the international law.
</P>
<P>
All international organizations and governments, especially
Lebanon, should do their utmost to force Israel to release the
Iranians, the spokesman stressed.
</P>
<P>
Expressing sympathy with the families of the kidnapped, Asefi
noted the Iranian Foreign Ministry is seriously following the case
and would spare no efforts to help them return.
</P>
<P>
The four Iranians were believed to be kidnapped on July 4, 1982
by the Phalangist Party, a right-wing Maronite Christian militant
group which fought with Palestinian guerrillas in the civil
violence and civil war in Lebanon in the 1970s and 1980s, and later
transferred to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Iran has refused to recognize the legitimacy of Israel since the
1979 Islamic revolution. It also calls for armed struggle to
liberate all the Arab lands under Israeli occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
