<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Personal computer sales have soured in Turkey this
year due to appealing payment terms and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time in Turkey that 180,000 personal computers
were sold in the first three months of the year. Computers that
used to be office equipment in the past are reaching homes and
schools now," said Selami Kaplan, General manager of Vestel
Bilisim, a leading Turkish PC maker.
</P>
<P>
Vestel Bilisim sold 100,000 PCs in 1999.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Foundations for four power plants tendered in 1997
under build-own-operate (BOO) model will be laid this month.
</P>
<P>
The new power plants will generate approximately 26.6 billion
kilowatt-hours of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
The three international consortia that will build the power
plants have settled financing issues.
</P>
<P>
Turkey witnessed a severe power shortage last winter which
resulted in frequent power cuts in homes.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Emirates Airline of the United Arab Emirates
announced Sunday the launch of non-stop flights to Chennai, south
India, starting from September 1.
</P>
<P>
The Dubai-Chennai route will have four flights every week, on
Monday, Wednesday, Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The new service is a major development in the airline's
passenger and cargo services to India. Air India will share with
Emirates Airline on all flights.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman Air will launch direct flights from Salalah in
Oman's scenic southern Dhofar region to Dubai, the UAE, this month
to cope with the anticipated increase in tourists from neighboring
countries for the annual Salalah Khareef Festival, Oman's biggest
tourism festival.
</P>
<P>
The festival, from July 23 to August 31, will coincide with a
variety of programs depicting the heritage and culture of Oman.
</P>
<P>
That Salalah has emerged as a holiday hub is evident by the fact
that it registered a 30-percent increase in tourist arrivals last
year, climbing from 87,805 visitors in 1998 to 113,920 in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
