<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Military Urged to Defend Sovereignty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has called upon the Armed Forces in the country to rise to the
challenges of defending the sovereignty and nascent democracy of
the country, The Post Express newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, represented by Defense Minister Theophilus Yakubu
Danjuma at the graduation ceremony of the Command and Staff
College in Kaduna over the weekend, noted that the recent events
in some parts of the country have made the statutory roles of the
armed forces enormous and most challenging.
</P>
<P>
The present administration is conscious of its responsibilities
to protect the citizens of the country which the government will
not compromise, he said, stressing that the task and challenges
before the armed forces are getting increasingly widened, and
therefore, professionally challenging.
</P>
<P>
"Our Armed Forces need to continuously redress, adopt and
develop their professional capabilities to retain their relevance
and effectiveness in the discharge of their role of defending the
territorial integrity of the nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He advised that the training and retraining of the armed forces
should be geared towards military professionalism.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve this, the government is placing emphasis on
the rationalization and re-equipment of the armed forces in
addition to enhancing the welfare of the officers and men, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a newly restructured armed forces is expected to
be capable of responding more effectively and efficiently to any
crisis within and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
"We shall continue to count on the loyalty, patriotism and
support of the officers and men of our armed forces as we strive
to fulfill our electoral promises as a people-oriented
government," he said. 
</P>
