<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Consumers Enjoy Good Ice-cream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The latest official random sampling
of ice-cream products in Beijing shows that ice-cream lovers in
this national capital are much luckier than residents of Harbin,
the only other city investigated at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The sampling shows that 85.4 percent of ice-cream sold in
Beijing consists of quality products, while in Harbin, the capital
of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, the figure is merely
41.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Quality and Technical Supervision
Administration conducted the surveys in the two major ice-cream
markets in China.
</P>
<P>
A total of 95 kinds of ice-cream products manufactured by 66
companies were sampled, of which 64.2 were up to standard,
compared with 64 percent and 41.7 percent in 1997 and 1999,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
China's domestic demand for ice-cream has been increasing
rapidly in recent years, and the growing market has attracted many
foreign investors and manufacturers to set up solely-funded
company or joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Local ice-cream factories have been increasing their outputs
and making new products by expanding capacity and upgrading
equipment.
</P>
<P>
In a news release, the state bureau criticized some local ice-
cream manufacturers for poor management, unhygienic conditions,
and low sense of quality and standardization. It urged local
quality and technical supervision authorities to punish ice-cream
factories that violate the state's hygiene standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Computer Giant Eyes World's Top 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Legend Group, China's largest
computer maker, announced today it will work to become among the
world's Top 500, which are selected by the U.S.-based Fortune
magazine every year, in the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious plan of the computer company, which was set up by
its president Liu Chuanzhi 15 years ago with a start-up fund of
500,000 yuan (about 60,000 U.S. dollars), will increase its sales
to more than 10 billion U.S. dollars from last year's 2.3 billion
U.S. dollars, a company spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the group sold 1.25 million computers, an increase
of 80 percent over the previous year, ranking itself first in the
Asia-Pacific region, replacing IBM and Compaq, and 13th in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The company's Hong Kong arm, Legend Holdings Ltd., was valued
at 900 million HK dollars when it was first listed nine years ago,
but now it boats a market capitalization of over 66 billion HK
dollars. Last year its sales reached 1.5 billion U.S. dollars, up
by 98 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences is the largest stock-holder of
the Legend Group, taking more than half of the group's shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
