<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CSFB Upgrades GDP Forecasts for Asian Nations in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Credit Suisse First Boston (
CSFB) announced Monday that it has revised its year 2000 GDP
forecasts for China, India, Hong Kong and Malaysia to 8 percent, 8
percent, 7 percent and 9 percent, respectively, up from the
previous 7.1 percent, 7.1 percent, 4.9 percent and 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In its third quarter report of Asian economies, CSFB, a leading
global investment banking firm, said GDP growth rates in most
Asian economies have peaked in the first quarter of 2000 and will
moderate in the rest of the year as statistical base returns to
the norm.
</P>
<P>
The bank's economists attributed the positive outlook to the
temporary peak of U.S. interest rate cycle, firm electronics
demand and subdued inflation.
</P>
<P>
CSFB argues that overheated economy in the U.S. in the first
quarter of 2000 was largely driven by Y2K related excess liquidity.
</P>
<P>
As the liquidity deflated, the U.S. economy has already slowed
down to about 3.5 percent, putting an end to the Fed tightening
for this year.
</P>
<P>
For Asian economies that are sensitive to U.S. interest rate
differentials, namely Hong Kong, Indonesia and the Philippines,
the immediate pressure to follow U.S. movements has eased.
</P>
<P>
A soft landing in the U.S. means a smaller correction in Asian
exports to the U.S., which have played a critical role in the
region's rebound in 1999, said the CSFB economists.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate cycle is also expected to have a stabilizing
effect on the U.S. stock market, which will in turn increase risk
appetites towards emerging markets, including Asia.
</P>
<P>
Electronic exports, accounting for 30 to 60 percent of total
exports in most Asian countries, except China and Indonesia,
showed solid growth despite some volatility in the fist quarter.
</P>
<P>
However, CSFB economists noted that U.S. electronics inventory
growth is now approaching levels that usually signal inflection
points in the new order cycle, which may imply a slower 2001.
</P>
<P>
Domestic consumption in most Asian economies is still on the
recovery path compared with levels in 1997 before the financial
crisis. Rising oil prices pose little threat to inflation as the
weighting of oil in the Consumption Price Index baskets of most
Asian economies is restrained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
