<HEADLINE> Israeli Troops Prepare for Possible Riots: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli troops are embracing for
riots and violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the coming
weeks surrounding a Palestinian declaration of statehood, an
Israeli newspaper said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Ha'aretz said IDF (Israeli Defense
Forces) is preparing vehicles, helicopters and tanks to confront
possible violent clashes with Palestinians in another popular
uprising, or Intifada.
</P>
<P>
It said the Israeli army has predicted that an imminent
unilateral Palestinian declaration of independence in September may
spark riots in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Army intelligence assessments view clashes with Palestinian
protestors as "inevitable," saying the only unknown factor is the
timing.
</P>
<P>
As the September deadline for the signing of a comprehensive and
permanent peace deal draws near, frustration among Palestinians
over the deadlock in peace negotiations is building up.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat has
threatened to leave for Tunis or Cairo to let Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak deal with the angry Palestinians, who have
threatened another Intifada.
</P>
<P>
Intifada was a seven-year Palestinian uprising in the 1980s
against Israeli occupation. In response, Israeli Chief of Staff
Shaul Mofaz warned that his troops are prepared to use helicopters
and tanks to confront violent clashes.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Central Council of the Palestinian
Liberation Organization (PLO) convened in Gaza for a two-day
session to discuss possible dates for a unilateral declaration of
the Palestinian state. The Palestinian leaders are expected to make
a decision on the issue on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who has repeatedly vowed to declared a Palestinian state
within the 1967 borders with east Jerusalem as its capital, is
under pressure from the people and the PLO leadership to do so in
September.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that Arafat would still prefer to reach a permanent
agreement with Israel rather than to unilaterally proclaim
statehood.
</P>
<P>
An Israel Radio report Monday quoted Oded Eran, head of the
Israeli team on final status talks, as saying that the two sides
have begun to discuss water, one of the thorniest issue to be
settled before a permanent peace deal ca be reached.
</P>
<P>
There have also been press leaks of developments in the peace
talks, but none has been officially confirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
