<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians to Get Jordan Valley Water Rights: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians are to get water
rights of the Jordan River and Lake Kinneret (Sea of Ghalili) if
Israel transfers the sovereignty of the Jordan Valley to them,
Israel's Ha'aretz daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting experts on water rights and international law, the
report said the handover of sovereignty over the Jordan River bank
will automatically entitle the Palestinians to part of the Jordan
River's water.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Israel is also obliged to provide the Palestinians a
quid pro quo from the water of Lake Kinneret, Israel's major fresh
water reservoir, as some water of the Jordan River flows into the
Lake. Thus, the Palestinians will have indirect access to the
Kinneret in legal terms.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan Valley was occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
War. It represents some 22 percent of the West Bank territory,
which is to be transferred to the Palestinians in a planned final
peace accord between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
In current Israeli-Palestinian talks, negotiators are discussing
the sovereignty transfer over the Jordan Valley. Israeli Deputy
Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh acknowledged last month that the
government is ready to give up part of the Valley, although it
hopes to retain a military presence there to safeguard Israel's
security interests.
</P>
<P>
Another version of rumors speculated that the Valley will be
announced as a security zone for a predetermined period, at the end
of which the two sides will decide on the area's sovereignty
finally.
</P>
<P>
Since 1967, Israel controls all the water sources in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. Even after the Palestinian National Authority
was established in the 1990s, Israel continues to control all water
resources on which the Palestinians depend.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1993 Oslo accords, the Palestinians received
water allocation from Israeli water system. However, Palestinian
and Israeli water authority officials routinely trade accusations
and conflicting data over water allocations every summer.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians accused that Israel supplied less water than it
is supposed to do, while Israeli officials admitted that "it is
inconceivable that water quantities should be cut in Israel when
they can easily be cut in the West Bank instead."
</P>
<P>
Israelis have an average water supply of 270 liters a day while
the Palestinians have only 70 liters a day.
</P>
<P>
During the dire water shortage in the region this summer, a
senior official of the Palestinian Water Authority had stated that
Israel dropped water supply to Palestinian areas by about 30
percent of what had been agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Israeli human rights groups joined local Palestinians
in a protest against Israel's discriminatory water policy, waving
posters reading "Palestinian thirst, (Jewish) Settlers swim."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Introduce mtDNA Technique for Human Identification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will introduce the
mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) technique soon to make easier the
solving of criminal cases, Science, Technology and Environment
Minister Law Hieng Ding said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Chemistry Department is making initial preparation to
introduce the new forensic DNA profiling technique, he told
reporters in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will be among the earliest countries in this region to
introduce the new mtDNA technique, first discovered in the United
States in 1996 which will help the police, he said.
</P>
<P>
The technique can be used in cases where the quantity of
biological evidence such as skeletal remains or degraded hair is
too small.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his government has allocated three million
ringgit (0.78 million U.S. dollars) to enable the Chemistry
Department to send scientists and experts in the relevant fields
to attend short courses abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said the department is actively building up its data bank
for DNA analysis samples known as DNA-STR for Bumiputeras (
aboriginals in Sabah and Sarawak, East Malaysia, to be made into
samples for reference in forensic cases.
</P>
<P>
He said "So far, analysis of samples for the Kadazan-Dusun and
Murut communities in Sabah are completed while samples for the
Iban, Bidayuh and Melanau communities in Sarawak are being
analyzed."
</P>
<P>
The work was expected to be completed by the end of the year
and would be extended to cover samples of other communities
including the Orang Asli and 56 other sub-groups in Sarawak and
other sub-groups in Sabah, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the data bank for the Malay, Chinese
and Indian communities of the country has already been established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
