<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't to Arrest Provocateurs, Rioter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said Monday that the government will immediately arrest
provocateurs and rioters who have made disturbances in various
areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
"I have ordered Chief of the National Police (Polri) and Chief
of the Indonesian Military (TNI) to do so (arrest provocateurs) by
July 15, at the latest," the president said in Medan, capital of
North Sumatra province.
</P>
<P>
"The provocateurs have to be arrested, we can not just let them
free to incite the riots," reports reaching here quoted the
president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Minister of Defense Juwono Sudarsono said that
there are strong indications that some elite politicians in
Jakarta are involved in communal bloodshed in Ambon, capital of
the country's Maluku province. They provided weapons and money to
the rioters, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The indications of their involvement are strong. But the
Police has not yet had strong evidences to arrest the provocateurs
of the riots. Based on law, it is difficult to be proven," the
minister was quoted by Suara Pembaruan daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also said the communal bloodshed in Ambon was triggered by
political conflicts which have been taking place in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the ongoing riots in the country have
something to do with the ongoing process of investigation into
former president Soeharto in corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cabinet Secretary Marsilam Simanjuntak confirmed
here Monday that some members of the House of Representatives (DPR)
and the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) are undergoing
investigation over alleged involvement in the riots in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Simanjuntak said ,"There are reports
from security elements in connection with a possible involvement
of some parties in the riots, including members of the DPR and the
MPR," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier President Wahid also said that he has signed a letter
to allow prosecutors of the Attorney General Office (AGO) to
examine members of the DPR and the MPR who are suspected to be
involved in the riots.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people have been killed in communal bloodshed
involving Muslims and Christians in the country's provinces of
Maluku, North Maluku, and Poso (a city in Central Sulawesi
province) since the Maluku violence broke out 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
On June 26, President Wahid announced a civil emergency in
Maluku and North Maluku provinces in a bid to end the clashes
between Muslims and Christians. Reports said the situation in
Maluku has been relatively calm since the imposition of the civil
emergency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
