<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
Chinese archaeological news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- Neolithic Axe Discovered in NW China
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists discovered a stone hand axe believed to
be from the Neolithic Age at a site of the Qijia Culture in
northwest China's Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
The artifact, which experts said was probably used as a musical
instrument for special rituals, was of great value to the study of
an early state's origin, according to Professor Xu Xinguo,
director of the Qinghai Provincial Archaeological Research
Institute. The axe weighs 35 kilograms, is 90 centimeters long and
60 cm wide. It produced a rhythmic sound when knocked.
</P>
<P>
-- 20,000 Ancient Coins Unearthed from Bottom Of Lake
</P>
<P>
China recently unearthed over 20,000 ancient coins during the
dredging of West Lake in the picturesque city of Hangzhou in east
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The coins belonged to several dynasties, the earliest dating
backing to the Warring States Period (B.C. 475-221).
</P>
<P>
Numismatists and archaeologists from both at home and abroad
have shown great interests in these coins, some of which are rare.
The coins show little signs of rust as they have long been kept in
water without any contact with the air.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing to Host Int'l Symposium on Relics Protection
</P>
<P>
An international symposium to find some solutions for China's
dilemma of rapid urbanization vs. relics protection will be held
July 5-7 in the Chinese capital, the State Administration of
Cultural Heritage (SACH) announced on June 30.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, "Cultural Relics Protection and Urban
Development in China: Opportunity and Challenge," is the first of
its kind in China, a 5,000-year-old country which is undergoing
breakneck urban construction amid economic booms.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting will be officials and specialists who are
responsible for relics protection and urban planning in dozens of
Chinese cities, as well as foreign experts invited by the World
Bank and the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Recovered National Treasure Put on Show in Beijing
</P>
<P>
An ongoing antique show in the Capital Museum in Beijing
features a national treasure that was looted by the British and
French troops in 1860 and recovered at an auction fair overseas.
</P>
<P>
The national treasure, a Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) hexagonal
porcelain vase, was purchased by the Beijing Cultural Relics
Company for 20.95 million Hong Kong dollars at an auction fair in
Hong Kong in early May. There are also another 30 precious Chinese
antiques the company recovered from overseas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
-- Huge Buddhist Collection Published
</P>
<P>
The imperial edition of a huge Buddhist collection has been
published by a Beijing publishing house.
</P>
<P>
The Yongle North Collection, widely regarded as the most
important sutra publication produced by the imperial court of the
Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), is now available to everyone.
</P>
<P>
The 200-volume collection has a nationwide circulation of 100
sets. As an imperial treasure in the Ming court, the block-print
North Collection was carefully preserved by court officials and
rarely seen by the common people.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing to Host Large Exhibition of Dunhuang Art
</P>
<P>
A large-scale exhibition scheduled to open in the Chinese
capital on July 4 will give modern city dwellers a taste of
Buddhist art from more than 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Art Exhibition, garnering dozens of precious
relics originating from Dunhuang in northwest China's Gansu
Province, will be unveiled at the Museum of Chinese History on the
east side of Tian'anmen Square in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The two-month show, the world's biggest to highlight Dunhuang
art, is part of the commemorative activities for the centennial
anniversary of the discovery of the Dunhuang Sutra Cave.
</P>
<P>
-- Returned Dunhuang Relics Under Good Protection
</P>
<P>
A Chinese expert said that eight Dunhuang relics donated by a
Japanese three years ago are now under protection.
</P>
<P>
Shi Pingting, an expert of Dunhuang Studies, said that the
eight relics are of great value in studying conditions and custom,
Buddhist art and the development of the handicraft industry in
Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
Among the returned relics is a list of expenditures on
alcoholic drinks by feudal officials during the Song Dynasty (960-
1279). The returned piece tallies with one document kept at the
Dunhuang Research Academy. One more part of the list is still kept
overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
