<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IASA-SEAPAVAA Conference 2000 Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A conference of the International
Association of Sound and Audiovisual Archives (IASA) and the South
East Asia-Pacific Audio Visual Archives Association (SEAPAVAA)
opened here Monday zeroing in on the theme "A Future for the Past:
AV Archiving in the 3rd Millennium."
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference, hosted by the National Archives of
Singapore (NAS) and attended by some 180 participants from 40
countries and areas, is the first joint conference between IASA
and SEAPAVAA and the first time that IASA is holding a conference
in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the opening, Singapore Minister for Information
and the Arts and Minister for the Environment, Lee Yock Suan said
that the task to preserve significant audio-visual records of the
past for posterity is both facilitated and made more challenging
by rapid changes in technology, especially in info-communications
which have multiplied the volume of records generated by a
multitude of competing and complementary sources with their own
perspectives and priorities.
</P>
<P>
He said the audio-visual materials residing in many
repositories across the globe make up a gigantic and priceless
visual record of our human history, culture and heritage.
</P>
<P>
On challenges facing archivists in their work to document and
preserve the past for future generations, he highlighted the need
to build up professionalism in this fairly new area of audio-
visual archives and to see how new technology can be harnessed to
document and preserve important historical events, adding this
technology should also be used to disseminate this information to
as wide an audience as possible.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, participants will discuss a series of
issues covering the latest developments in the profession,
advancements on the technological front -- especially digital
technologies, and the future direction of audiovisual archiving.
</P>
<P>
A host of activities at the conference will complement the main
symposium and poster sessions, including the book launch of "Film
in Southeast Asia: Views from the Region" which presents the
history of film in Southeast Asia, Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
IASA, established in 1969 as a professional organization
specially devoted to sound archives, has about 380 members with
representations from some 50 countries and areas. SEAPAVAA
was founded in 1996 as an international non-governmental
association of organizations and individuals involved in or
interested in the development of audiovisual archiving in
Southeast Asia, Australia, New Zealand and the pacific islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
