<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Condemns U.S., Britain for Blocking Health Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Monday condemned the United
States and Britain for putting on hold 83 health contracts Iraq
signed with foreign countries over the past seven phases of the
United Nations oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
Health Minister Umid Medhat Mubarak said the U.S. and British
delegates at the U.N. Sanctions Committee are continuing the policy
of "fabricating fragile pretexts" to ban Iraq's imports of medicine
and medical appliances.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that this has dealt a blow to Iraq's plan to import
medicine worth 500 million U.S. dollars to alleviate the acute
shortage of medicine, which is estimated at 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The health minister added that 89 hospitals, 473 health centers
and four medical stores were destroyed in the 1991 Gulf War, which
put an end to Iraq's occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly condemned the U.S. and Britain for impeding
the implementation of the humanitarian oil-for-food program by
blocking its contracts, worsening the humanitarian crisis in Iraq
as a result of the decade-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
It claims that over 1.3 million people, mostly children and the
elderly, have died due to the crippling U.N. sanctions, imposed on
Iraq since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. oil-for-food program, launched in late 1996 and now in
its eighth phase, allows Iraq to sell limited amount of oil under
U.N. supervision to by humanitarian supplies, including food and
medicines.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has acknowledged the holding
of the contracts has had a direct negative impact on the oil-for-
food program and on the efforts to rehabilitate Iraq's
infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
