<HEADLINE> New Zealand FM Describes Fijian Interim Govt as "Unrepresentative" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Foreign Minister
Phil Goff has described the Fijian Interim Civilian Government as
"unrepresentative and lacking a mandate."
</P>
<P>
"The fact that it does not include Speight supporters is
welcome. The fact there are no Indo-Fijians on board is of great
concern," Goff said in a government press release.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's position remains that the 1997 Constitution and
the Parliament elected last year should be restored, he said,
adding "There are the only sources of legitimate power in Fiji."
</P>
<P>
"Our attitude to the new government will be determined by its
commitment to return Fiji to constitutional and democratic
processes. We are still waiting to hear their intentions in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
"At the very minimum the administration must set a clear time
table for the restoration of democracy and the fundamental rights
of all Fijians," he said.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand foreign minister said his immediate concern
remains the safe release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Suva, Fiji's military chief Commodore
Frank Bainimarama Monday named indigenous Fijian banker Laisenia
Qarase as interim prime minister, replacing Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry who has been held hostage by Speight and his
supporters following a coup on May 19.
</P>
<P>
He also announced at a news conference that there are no ethnic
Indians in the interim government, which will be appointed on
Tuesday and serve for up to two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
