<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds Of Zimbabwean Whites Returning Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of white Zimbabweans who
fled the country prior to the parliamentary election on June 24
and 25 started returning home at the weekend, The Herald newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Immigration officials at Beitbridge border crossing confirmed
the arrival of hundreds of whites and their families who had left
the country in fear of election-related violence.
</P>
<P>
Most of the whites interviewed in Beitbridge said they were
happy to return to Zimbabwe and were willing to work with the
government for the development of the country.
</P>
<P>
Political violence had been on the increase since February when
black war veterans began occupying hundreds of white-owned farms
to press for accelerating land redistribution.
</P>
<P>
"I am not sure what to say on the land issue but I feel if it
is not resolved it is a time-bomb. The land is our biggest problem
and not political differences. Blacks have every right to the
land," said a white commercial farmer who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
He said their two-week stay in South Africa was not as
comfortable and his family had not relaxed but constantly watched
proceedings of the election on television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
