<HEADLINE> Kenya and Uganda to Jointly Combat Border Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Kenya and Uganda
have ensured that all criminals escaping from either country will
be arrested ad handed over to their respective government, local
newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
At a recent high-level security meeting between the two
countries held in Uganda's Kapchorwa District, the participants
agreed that both countries ought to tackle common problems like
cattle rustling and flush out criminals who seek cross-border
asylum after committing crimes in either country.
</P>
<P>
The peaceful co-existence of communities living along the
border was essential for the development of the two countries,
they said.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to establish a free communication network
between the two countries as the most effective way of combating
crime.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Uganda had recently arrested and
repatriated a wanted Kenyan believed to be behind insecurity in
parts of northern Kenya, involving highway robbery, cattle
rustling and rape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
