<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Old Stone Age Animal Fossils Discovered in Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a batch of animal fossils and stone tools dating 100,
000 years ago during a recent excavation in the Three Gorges area
in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made at an Old Stone Age site at Jingshuiwan,
Fengdu County, which covers more than 3,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the ancient vertebrates and human beings research
institute under the Chinese Academy of Sciences believed that the
animal fossils belong to deer, ox, stegodon, tapir and others.
</P>
<P>
They said that it is rare to discover animal fossils in south
China, because acid soil there is detrimental to animal skeletons.
Fossilized deer and stegodon were also found in the area last year.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 stone tools unearthed there include cores, flakes,
choppers, scrapers and pointed implements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Building World's Largest Goose Liver Factory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China is building the world's
largest goose liver processing plant in its southern Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the factory, located in Beihai city, is
scheduled to be completed in four years with an investment of 10
million yuan (1.2 million U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
The plant is designed to produce 1,000 tons of goose liver
annually, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The goose liver is a delicious food popular in Europe and the
United States and annual demand for the goose liver has reached
more than 10,000 tons on the world market.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is best known for its Chinese geese, known as the "lion
head goose". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Popularizing Knowledge of Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- a long-term project aiming at
popularize Internet knowledge among Chinese people, especially
youngsters, has been launched recently here in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The project, named "1.2 billion people sharing the Internet",
is jointly sponsored by the Photo News Department of Xinhua News
Agency and the Langchao Group.
</P>
<P>
It involves opening Internet popularization schools in over 200
Chinese cities since July, teaching basic knowledge and technique
free of charge, as well as hosting public forums of information
technology and exhibitions of network equipment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the current 10 million Internet users
account for less than one percent of the country's total
population, and they mainly live in several metropolises, such as
Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the project attempts to narrow the gap between
Internet and the people, according to the sponsors of the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
