<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite the opposition of many coalition members, Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has a probable majority of the passage on
the first reading Monday of a bill that would turn the Tal
Commission recommendations on army service deferrals for ultra-
orthodox students into law.
</P>
<P>
In a vote of 12-2 with one abstention, the cabinet Sunday
decided after a five-and-a-half-hour debate to adopt the
recommendations of the commission, and bring the bill to the
Knesset (parliament) for a vote.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which is intended to grant the ultra-orthodox students
special rights to study in the yeshiva theological colleges, has
drawn strong protests from Israeli students.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- By transferring sovereignty over the Jordan Rift Valley to
the Palestinians, Israel will grant them the right to some water
from the Jordan River and Lake Kinneret (or Sea of Galilee) under
certain conditions, according to analyses by experts on water
rights and international law, and officers on the Israeli Defense
Forces's General Staff, that have been passed on to Prime Minister
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
The experts hold that the transfer of sovereignty to the
Palestinian National Authority up to the Jordan River bank will
have implications that go far beyond the security aspect of an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli Mossad intelligence agent caught in Switzerland
in 1998 attempting to bug the home of a Hezbollah (or Party of God)
representative returned to Bern to stand trial on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak Ben Tal, as the agent is known, had been released on
bail from Switzerland until the date of his trial. He faces a
maximum penalty of three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Council of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization (PLO) are to decide Monday whether or not to declare a
Palestinian state on September 13. This is the third time the
council has met since April 1999 to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat, who has
repeatedly promised to declare a Palestinian state within the 1967
borders with east Jerusalem as its capital, is under pressure from
the people and the PLO leadership to do so in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
