<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Radio Signal Reaches Central Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Residents in central Israel can
tune in to a new frequency modulation radio station in recent days.
What is worth mentioning is that the signal was aired by Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas, Israel's nemesis during its two-decade
occupation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel erected a so-called security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985, Hezbollah, a Shiite Muslim militia backed by Iran and
Syria, had spearheaded the armed resistance in Lebanon which
finally spurred Israel to pull out of Lebanon in May.
</P>
<P>
As the Lebanese government has not sent its troops to the
Israeli-evacuated south, the former security zone is virtually
under the control of Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
After the Israeli withdrawal, Nur, the Hezbollah radio station,
had reportedly increased its broadcasting range to 95.9 FM. Israeli
sources said that the signal could be picked up loud and clear
Sunday morning in Israel's central region, despite occasional
slight disruptions.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the frequency seemed to have been occupied by a
nearby Hebrew radio station.
</P>
<P>
Through the radio wave, Hezbollah launched a new public relation
war against Israelis. Most of the radio's programs were religious
sermon, news, and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
It also lauds the resistance of Islamic fighters and mourns the
fallen soldiers during the fighting against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of the Lebanese still being held in Israeli prisons
were interviewed, saying that they are looking forward to their
family members' return home.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners recently released by Israel also accused Israeli
prison administration with brutal torture.
</P>
<P>
There are still some Lebanese prisoners held by Israeli
government, and Hezbollah had urged Israelis to release them as
soon as possible. Otherwise, the militia said, it will pick up its
weapons again to make Israelis' life difficult. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interim Govt Doesn't Represent Fiji: New Zealand PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister Helen
Clark said here Monday that Fiji's interim civilian administration
does not include Fijians of Indian origin and women, and on that
basis, it "cannot be seen as representative of the country,"
according to Television NZ.
</P>
<P>
Clark was also quoted as saying that New Zealand is not usually
required to give formal recognition to another country's
government, but she will be looking to see what sort of commitment
the Fiji interim administration has to make in restoring democracy.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Suva, Fiji's military chief Commodore
Frank Bainimarama Monday named indigenous Fijian banker Laisenia
Qarase as interim prime minister, replacing Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry who has been held hostage by the rebels
following a coup on May 19.
</P>
<P>
He also announced at a news conference that there are no ethnic
Indians in the interim government, which will be appointed on
Tuesday and serve for up to two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
