<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox Wins Mexico's Presidential Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Vicente Fox from the opposition
National Action Party won Mexico's presidential elections held on
Sunday, according to initial results.
</P>
<P>
"The Federal Electoral Institute (FEI) has told us it has
reliable information to know that the new president of the
republic will be Vicente Fox, whom I contacted in order to
congratulate him," President Ernesto Zedillo was quoted by a radio
report.
</P>
<P>
Fox's major rival, Francisco Labastida, of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, has acknowledged his defeat in
the elections, the first for the ruling party in 71 years.
</P>
<P>
Fox, 58, once a Coca-Cola executive and governor of central
Guanajuato state, has won 45 percent of the votes with 51 percent
of the total vote tallied, said media reports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the results announced by the FEI, an
independent election watchdog, the coalition of the National
Action Party and the Green Party also has big possibility to win
the parliamentary elections held together with the presidential
elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Out of 18 percent of the voted counted, the alliance gained
some 42 percent of the votes for the lower house and more than 41
percent for the Senate, or the upper house.
</P>
<P>
More than 45 million eligible voters went for the voting with
the balloting rate standing at some 75 percent, said the FEI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
