<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Fiji's military leaders are finalizing the interim
government line-up and said it should be ready on Wednesday, the
Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The military authorities have confirmed that it will appoint
ethnic Indians to the new interim government, the ABC said. The
interim government will rule until new elections in about two
years and have a mandate to address longer term issues such as
land ownership and economic growth. The ABC quoted military
spokesman Filip Tarakinikini as saying some previous government
candidates were reluctant to serve in the new cabinet because of
fears for their safety, so the military will provide ongoing
protection. (Australia-Fiji)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- European Commission President Romano Prodi warned
Sunday that the European Union must push ahead with enlargement or
risk seeing the continent split in two again.
</P>
<P>
"We can't take responsibility for the rebirth of a Berlin Wall,
" he told a seminar in the central Italian town of Arezzo, urging
Italy, a founding member of the EU, to play a full role in calling
for enlargement and act as a counter-weight in French and German-
led plans for speedier EU integration. "It's a grandiose and
unprecedented design to create the world' s greatest economic
reality with democracy and respect for the individual countries'
diversity," said Prodi. (Italy-EU Prodi)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Vicente Fox from the opposition won Mexico's
presidential elections, President Ernesto Zedillo said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Labastida of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party has acknowledged his defeat in the elections, the first for
the ruling party in 71 years. The Federal Electoral Institute, an
independent election watch dog, announced that Fox from the
National Action Party has won between 39 and 45 percent of the
vote. (Mexico-General Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Former senator and head of the Fiji Development
Bank, Laisenia Qarase, was named Fiji's prime minister Monday
afternoon, fijilive.com website said.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen ministers and one assistant minister of the interim
civilian government were also announced by Fiji's military leader
Frank Bainimarama, the website said. (Australia-Fiji) 
