<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Across Board in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose across the board in
Tokyo Monday on widespread optimism over a recovery in the
Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 203.61 points, or 1.17
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 17,614.66, finishing
above 17,600 for the first time in almost eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 11.91 points, or 0.75 percent, to 1,
603.51.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section expanded to 1,017.11 million
shares from last Friday's 872.14 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information technology (IT) issues were boosted by
last Friday's gain on Wall Street and the yen's weakness against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Expectations that the Tankan business confidence survey by the
Bank of Japan on Tuesday will clearly show a recovery in the
economy also urged investors to buy stocks in various sectors, a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The mining, brokerage, construction sectors were higher, while
banks and nonbank moneylenders were down, hit by fears over the
possible end of the central bank's zero-interest-rate policy,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers far exceeded
losers 1,081 to 269, with 51 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
