<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Lead - Former Senator to Head Fiji Interim Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Former senator and head of the
Fiji Development Bank, Laisenia Qarase, was named Fiji's prime
minister Monday afternoon, fijilive.com website reported.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen ministers and one assistant minister of the interim
civilian government were also announced by Fiji's military
commander Frank Bainimarama, the website said.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama said two Indian Fijians were offered posts on the
interim cabinet but both declined the offer, the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted Bainimarama as saying the interim cabinet will
have a wide ranging mandate, including the rehabilitation of Fiji'
s economy, affirmative action programs for indigenous Fijians and
the contentious issue of the land ownership.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet team was chosen because of their high
standing in the community, the professionalism and their
qualifications.
</P>
<P>
On the cabinet list announced by Bainimarama former army
commander and Ambassador to Britain Ratu Epeli Nailatikau was
named deputy prime minister and minister for Fijian affairs,
according to the fijilive.com.
</P>
<P>
Former Governor of the Reserve Bank of Fiji Ratu Jone Kubuabola
will become minister for finance, public enterprises and national
planning.
</P>
<P>
Former ambassador to the European Commission Kaliopate Tavola
will serve as minister for foreign affairs, external trade and
sugar.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet will be officially sworn in Tuesday and will
take over from the military council to rule the country for the
next 18 months, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Qarase has already held talks with foreign missions, including
Australia's high commissioner, to secure international recognition,
the ABC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
