<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Awaits U.S. Ratification of Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
awaiting the U.S. ratification of a bilateral extradition treaty
which will pave the way for extraditing perpetrators of terrorism,
the official Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The treaty addresses, in particular, serious international
crimes such as acts of terrorism," said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, replacing a 1931 treaty signed by Britain as the
colonial power on behalf of Sri Lanka, was signed in Washington on
September 30, 1999, by Sri Lankan Minister of Foreign Affairs
Lakshman Kadirgamar and U.S. Acting Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton last Thursday forwarded the much
awaited treaty to the Senate for its advice and consent.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka considers the new treaty a major international
victory over the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels
who have been waging a 17-year civil war to carve out a separate
state called Eelam for minority Tamils in the country's north and
east.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been designated by the U.S. State Department as a
terrorist organization and was banned at home as well as in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which has a sizable Sri Lankan Tamil
expatriate community, has long been considered one of the more
powerful international bases of the LTTE rebels where they take
refuge to collect funds and negotiate for arms and other supplies
for its war efforts.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will mean that LTTE rebels who try to hide in the
United States after committing a crime could be sent back and
brought to book in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
