<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Disperse Opposition Party's Celebration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's special police and army
units dispersed a celebration by the opposition Movement for
Democratic Change (MDC) in Harare suburb on Sunday,saying any
large political gatherings have been temporarily banned in areas
considered to be trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
Several MDC supporters sustained varying degrees of injury
after they were allegedly beaten up by the law enforcers at the
gathering, the Herald newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Chief Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena was
quoted as saying the police and army officers had acted within
their legal limits in breaking up the party since avoiding
post-election political violence remained their top security
priority.
</P>
<P>
"What we are doing is discouraging any party from having any
demonstrations due to the volatility in the suburbs," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 30 people have been arrested for post-electoral violence
in Harare and Kwekwe, a city in the middle of the country since
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newly formed MDC won 57 of the 120 contested seats in the
parliamentary elections on June 24-25. 
</P>
