<HEADLINE> China Reviewing Trade Laws to Prepare for WTO Entry: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's law-makers are busy
reviewing the country's foreign trade laws and regulations to see
if they conform to the World Trade Organization rules, China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quated Shi Guangsheng, minister of foreign trade and
economic cooperation (MOFTEC), as saying that all the laws,
regulations and policies concerning foreign trade and investment
will be reviewed for possible revisions and even repeal.
</P>
<P>
Possible revisions will go through the legislative procedures,
and the revised drafts of three laws on overseas-invested ventures
have been submitted to the State Council, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Shi said as the country's WTO entry is "not far away," China is
required to reevaluate its foreign business laws and regulations
to keep promises it has made to WTO members.
</P>
<P>
The drafts of new laws, such as the anti-dumping and anti-
subsidy codes, are ready for submission, and the country is also
drafting laws to complete its foreign trade and investment-related
legal framework, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that transparency of laws and regulations, an
improved business environment, and a system to timely notify
investors of policy changes are like to make China's market more
attractive.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report said all industries and sectors of the
country are examining possible measures to meet challenges and not
to miss opportunities brought by its entry into the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
