<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Surplus Narrows in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia continued to register
a trade surplus in May 2000, but the surplus narrowed as compared
with that in the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In May, the 31 consecutive month for Malaysia to record trade
surplus since November 1997, a trade surplus of 4.5 billion
ringgit (1.18 billion U.S. dollars) was recorded against 6.5
billion ringigt (1.71 billion U.S. dollars) in the same month of
last year, according to figures released here Monday by the
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in the month under review was achieved despite a
higher import growth of 36.7 percent against that of exports of 19.
7 percent, the department said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Total exports and imports in May amounted to 30.7 billion
ringgit (8.07 billion U.S. dollars) and 26.1 billion ringgit (6.86
billion U.S. dollars) respectively against 25.6 billion ringgit (6.
73 billion U.S. dollars) in exports and 19.1 billion ringgit (5.02
billion U.S. dollars) in imports in May 1999, the statistics
showed.
</P>
<P>
Over the first five month this year, Malaysia posted a trade
surplus of 24.5 billion ringgit (6.44 billion U.S. dollars), which
was also smaller than a trade surplus of 28.2 billion ringgit (7.
42 billion U.S.dollars) recorded in the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
