<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Deploys 20 Ships to Save Eastern Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Navy is deploying 20
patrol ships in eastern Indonesian waters to save its marine
resources which are susceptible to poaching, a naval officer said
in Jayapura, capital of Irian Jaya province.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Jayapura Naval Base Commodore Franklin W.
Kayjattu said the 20 ships left the naval base of the Indonesian
eastern fleet in Surabaya, East Java, for the eastern Indonesian
waters on June 26.
</P>
<P>
The warships are the large ones, such as KRI Multa Tuli with a
crew of 190, and the smaller ones such as fast patrol boats with a
crew of 60 to 90.
</P>
<P>
"The waters of Maluku and Irian Jaya which are rich in marine
resources have always become a haven for poachers so that many
ships are needed to patrol the waters," Kayjattu was quoted by the
Antara News Agency Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Many Thai-and Philippine-registered fishing vessels have been
detained by the Indonesian Navy in these waters for illegally
catching fish and shrimps.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a naval patrol boat caught seven foreign fishing
vessels, all flying the Philippine flag, in eastern Indonesian
waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
