<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Tries to Solve Burmese Refugee Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will try to send as many
Burmese refugees as possible home within next few years, a senior
official was quoted by Monday's Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
National Security Council chief Khachadpai Burusapatana stated
that Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai will meet Burmese leaders
to discuss the issue during an informal summit of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) later this year.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, the government is also urging The United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to do more than merely
giving assistance to Burmese refugee camps in Thailand, " said
Khachadpai, who had accompanied Chuan to visit the Ban Ma La
refugee camp Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The camp, situated at the Tak Province, 426 kilometers
Northwest of Bangkok, houses 30,711 of over 100,000 Burmese
refugees living in five Thai border provinces.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes the UNHCR to help solve the refugee
problem by opening a dialogue with the Burmese government, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR regional representative for Thailand Jahansha Assadi said
the U.N. agency is already in contact with the Burmese government
about the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
He also praised Chuan's visit to the camp, saying it showed
Thailand's humanitarian commitment to the refugees and the
importance it attached to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
