<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Clash in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Open clashes erupted again in Ambon,
capital of Indonesia's Maluku province, over the weekend,
shattering days of calm since the civil emergency status took
effect on June 27.
</P>
<P>
The incident broke out Saturday noon at the Poka and Rumahtiga
subdistrict, 21 kilometers north of Ambon, and continued until
late on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At least one person died and four others were injured in the
clash. Dozens of houses and government buildings, including the
poly technique building of Pattimura University, the university's
housing complex and a high school were burned during the clash.
</P>
<P>
"Masses from both warring camps came face to face before people
from the neighboring predominantly Muslim Jasirah Leihutu
subdistrict attacked Poka and Rumahtiga area. We immediately
called for help from the Pattimura Military chief because no
troops were available here," Rev. Ferry Nahusona of the Sejahtera
Poka Church crisis center was quoted by the Jakarta Post Monday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Security forces from the 509th Battalion of the Army's
Strategic Reserved Command and the local military command were
immediately deployed to quell the fray.
</P>
<P>
The death toll rose to 71 since violence returned in Ambon on
June 21. Hundreds have been injured during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
