<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Starts Safety Check on Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The check will consist of supervising the implementation of a
boat safety management responsibility system at the county and
rural township government levels, and standardize the granting of
business licenses for rural township passenger and ferry boats, "
China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Unlicensed boats, boats without enough crew members and skilled
pilots as well as being overloaded with people, goods or domestic
animals will be banned from operations. Sailing during foggy
conditions will be banned as well.
</P>
<P>
During an emergency telephone conference on water
transportation held here Friday, Huang Zhendong, Minister of
Communications, said that in a short period of 10 days plus in May,
seven boating accidents took place on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The most serious took place in Hejiang County, southwest China'
s Sichuan Province on June 22, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Sector Opens Wider: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's fledging auto industry will
open wider to foreign investments over the next five years to help
it survive and grow, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is indispensable for the country's auto
industry, which is short of funds and weak in product development,
said Jia Xingguang, a senior expert with the China National
Automotive Industry Consulting and Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
"The auto sector must use more foreign investment and follow
development technology to sharpen its competitive edge within the
buffer period after the country's WTO accession," he said.
</P>
<P>
China is to reduce tariffs on auto imports from 100 percent to
25 percent by mid-2006. Foreign automakers will be free to choose
models and types when producing automobiles in China, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Jia urged the government to further remove restrictions against
foreign investment instead of "koshering its auto sector."
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the State Administration of Machine-building
Industry showed that the industry has actually attracted a total
foreign investment of more than 5.2 billion U.S. dollars in more
than 600 joint ventures from 1981 to 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
