<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are today's
highlights of major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin Sunday in Beijing urged all
the parties involved in the Mideast peace process to take "serious
and concrete attitude" towards the process and earnestly implement
all the agreements reached so as to ensure the advance of the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks in a phone call from Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin has expressed deep concern
over the recent fireworks explosion in south China's Guangdong
Province, urging local governments to take immediate measures to
ensure industrial safety.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, at a fireworks factory at 8:05 am Friday in
Jiangmen City, claimed 36 lives, leaving 160 people injured and
more than 30 missing.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- Science and technology should be the driving force for China
's rejuvenation and sustainable development, President Jiang Zemin
writes in the June 30 issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
In an about-700-word editorial titled "Science in China", Jiang
says that "the Chinese government is committed to establishing a
favorable environment in which scientific creativity flourishes
along with innovative commercialization, and in which management
reform is a must."
</P>
<P>
-- Visiting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met German Federal
President Johannes Rau in Berlin on Saturday and discussed ways of
promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
 The German president welcomed Zhu's visit, saying he believes
the Chinese premier's current visit would push the bilateral ties
to an all-round development.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China's lawmakers are busy checking the country's laws,
regulations and policies concerning foreign trade and investment
to see if they conform to the World Trade Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
-- The long-standing monopoly of the telecommunications sector
has been broken in Shanghai with the sector's business being
divided into four separate entities to handle fix-lined phone
service, mobile telecom service, satellite telecom service and
paging services.  
</P>
