<HEADLINE> 15 Passengers Aboard Ill-fated Plane Updates with correction in figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 15 passengers were on
board the ill-fated 12-seat Nomad plane of the Philippine Air
Force which plunged into the Sulu water earlier Sunday, a local TV
station reported.
</P>
<P>
The ABS-CBN news channel said in an earlier report that 12
people were on board a nine-seat Nomad plane.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was flying from Cagayancillo town in the
southwestern province of Palawan to the provincial capital of
Puerto Princesa on a medical mission past 10 a.m., reportedly
experienced an engine trouble before it nose-dived into the waters
near Calusa island.
</P>
<P>
Among the passengers were Palawan Governor Salvador Socrates
and Armed Forces Western Command commander Maj. Gen. Santiago
Madrid who was confirmed dead, and one survivor, identified as
Bruce Walker, was rescued by local fishermen near the crash site.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations are still under way for possible survivors.
The military has formed a team to probe into the cause of the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Last April, a Boeing jet slammed into a tree-covered hill on
Samal island near the airport of the southern city of Davao,
killing all 131 people aboard in the country's worst air disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
