<HEADLINE> Fiji's Interim Govt to Be Announced Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's military leaders are
finalizing the interim government line-up and said it should be
ready on Wednesday, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC)
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The military authorities have confirmed that it will appoint
ethnic Indians to the new interim government, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
The interim government will rule until new elections in about
two years and have a mandate to address longer term issues such as
land ownership and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted military spokesman Filip Tarakinikini as saying
some previous government candidates were reluctant to serve in the
new cabinet because of fears for their safety, so the military
will provide ongoing protection.
</P>
<P>
"We will protect this government when they are sworn in to
ensure that nothing happens to them," he said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed plans for a military exclusion zone around the
country's parliament are still on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
"There has to be a lot of preparations that go into place and
that's just what the military is doing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tarakinikini also said he would prefer to let the hostage
crisis drag on than try anything that endangers the captives.
</P>
<P>
The 27 hostages, members of Fiji's elected government, are now
in their seventh week of captivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
