<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientist Suggests New Way of Understanding AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. genome scientist Monday
called for research to focus more on the role of the human genome
in AIDS, saying that the perspective could possibly provide new
methods of controlling AIDS progression.
</P>
<P>
"This new understanding of AIDS could be the first practical
application of the human genome project," said a statement by Dr.
Howard Urnovitz, scientific director of the Chronic Illness
Research Foundation and chief science officer of a California-
based biotech company.
</P>
<P>
Urnovitz's insight into the role of HIV into AIDS targets the
upcoming 13th International AIDS Conference to be held in Durban,
South Africa. One topic the conference will be addressed is the
decade old debate of what role the virus HIV plays in AIDS. More
than 5,000 scientists worldwide have signed a statement called the
Durban Declaration, resounding assertion that HIV causes AIDS and
calling for an immediate end to the debate on the fundamental
causal relationship between AIDS and HIV.
</P>
<P>
Instead of a classic viral disease, Urnovitz suggests AIDS is a
"host vs. genome disease" with an associated virus. The role of
HIV can best be described in computer science terms as a "router,"
he said. A router is a device that chooses the best pathway for
information to travel from one information network to another. HIV
appears to route new genomic code to CD4 T cells, the most common
cell eliminated in the course of AIDS progression.
</P>
<P>
Conventional wisdom is that HIV directly kills CD4 T cells.
Urnovitz said that research supports another mechanism where the
CD4 T cells are eliminated by the host's own immune cells, a
condition known as "graft vs. host" disease.
</P>
<P>
The missing link in AIDS research is the role the human genome
plays in the disease, according to the genome scientist, who
discovered the role of the human genome in veterans suffering from
Persian Gulf War Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
He describes the role of "poikilogenic" agents in chronic
diseases like AIDS. Poikilogens, from Greek for "generators of
diversity," have only recently been recognized due primarily to
the mapping of the human genome. Poikilogenic agents are those
toxic entities -- chemicals, radiological or biological -- that
create genetic diversity. The product of these agents is often the
creation of new genetic material reshuffled from the original
blueprint obtained from each parent.
</P>
<P>
According to Urnovitz, the most likely role of HIV in AIDS is
to route information of toxic exposures to CD4 T cells. The body's
own while blood cells attack the CD4 T cells that have been
exposed to these new genetic sequences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0324 </DOCNO>
