<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Program for Danube Delta Ends Successfully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) project for
the preservation of bio-diversity in the Danube Delta reached a
successful completion, reported the official Rompres news agency
on Monday, quoting WB officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The non-refundable financial assistance project, worth 4.5
million U.S. dollars, was signed with the World Bank in 1994 and
unfolded over five years in collaboration with the Romanian
Ministry of Woods and Environmental Protection, the Administration
of the Danube Delta Biosphere Reservation and the Danube Delta
National Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives were to increase environmental protection,
the drawing up of a program for the monitoring and inventory of
eco-systems and the restoring of 60,000-ha reed plantation.
</P>
<P>
The Natural Reservation of the Danube Delta encompasses 580,000
hectares, the equivalent of 2.5 percent of Romania's landmass, and
is the third in importance after the Amazon Delta and the Nile
Delta.
</P>
<P>
The Danube Delta area is home to hundreds of bird species and
it is the only sanctuary in the world which 176 of these species
can tolerate for nesting.
</P>
<P>
Rare birds like the red-collar duck, accounting for 90 percent
of the world population, the white egret, 71 percent, and the
Lilliputian cormorant, 61 percent, have found their home in the
Danube Delta area.
</P>
<P>
The waters of the Danube Delta accommodate numberless fishes,
of which some of industrial value, like carp, catfish, pike, and
migratory sturgeons.
</P>
<P>
In December 1990, the Natural Reservation of the River Danube
Delta was included by UNESCO into the world cultural heritage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
