<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25,000 Year-Old Archeological Site Discovered in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A group of archeologists from
France and Sao Paulo announced Monday, after 17 years of
investigation, the discovery of relics dating 25,000 years in
Brazil's central Mato Grosso state.
</P>
<P>
The archeological site, known as the second oldest in Brazil,
is found at Santa Elina Ranch, 80 kilometers from Cuiaba, capital
of the state.
</P>
<P>
At this place, cave paintings were found with images of men,
animals and other representations. According to archeologists,
cave painting was prehistoric people's way to communicate.
</P>
<P>
Also were discovered at the place local fragments of giant
sloth, extinct for about 10,000 years, and according to the bones,
one of these animals measured 3 meters in length.
</P>
<P>
The finding of the archeological site takes investigators to
the conclusion that the presence of man in Mato Grosso dates, at
least, 25,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The investigation's results, according to archeologists, are
basic for questioning regarding the arrival of man to America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000703.0329 </DOCNO>
