<HEADLINE> British Minister: Zimbabwe "May Need Emergency Food Aid" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain warned on Monday that
Zimbabwe could need emergency food aid within months.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office minister Peter Hain, who is responsible for
relations with Africa, said that Zimbabwe could soon face food
shortages as a result of the country's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe could need food aid within "a matter of months" unless
President Robert Mugabe's government changes its policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a real risk now, in fact a probability, of starvation
in a country that should comfortably be able to feed itself," he
told journalists.
</P>
<P>
Hain said he is concerned that the uncertainty over the farms
is having an impact on agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe, facing its worst economic crisis since
independence from Britain in 1980, was likely to see economic
output drop by 10 percent next year for a second year.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is increasing...to frightening levels," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Hain is scheduled to visit Africa from Tuesday.  
</P>
