<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Sends Reconnaissance Team to Eritrea, Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The mission, led by Major-General Timothy Ford of Australia,
included military, political, legal and humanitarian experts, U.N.
spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement coincided with the release of Annan's June 30
report to the Security Council in which he said the long-awaited
agreement signed on June 18 under the auspices of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) was an extremely vital step towards the
restoration of peace.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the mission will make recommendations on a concept
of operations for a U.N. peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
He is also sending liaison officers to the capitals of Eritrea
and Ethiopia to help plan the operation. Once the peacekeeping
force is approved by the Security Council, the officers would be
followed by military observer teams stationed in each capital.
</P>
<P>
Up to 100 U.N. military observers would gradually be deployed
in each country over the next two months.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief urged the two Horn of Africa neighbors to
cooperate fully with the OAU in the envisaged second phase of
proximity talks.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of war in May 1998 along a border poorly
demarcated after Eritrea's independence in 1993 has reportedly
cost over 100,000 lives. Five days after fighting was renewed on
May 12 this year, the Security Council imposed an arms embargo on
the two countries for 12 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
