<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish News Agencies Sign Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Athens News Agency (ANA)
and Turkey's Anatolian Agency (AA) signed here Monday an agreement
for cooperation in order to give the peoples of the two countries
more direct and fuller information regarding developments and
prospects in the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the first of its kind between the two news
agencies, was signed by ANA General Director Andreas
Christodoulides and his Turkish counterpart, Mehmet Guler.
</P>
<P>
The pact calls for the daily exchange of news items and
photographs, the exchange of know-how and experiences and joint
activities.
</P>
<P>
The two general directors stressed at the signing ceremony
that they would help improve relations between the two long-time
rivals and promote a peaceful approach in dealing with the
outstanding problems that continue to exist between them.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have nearly gone to war
three times in the past 26 years because of their territorial
dispute in the eastern Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem, but the
two neighbors have since last June taken steps to better their
strained relations by the holding of several rounds of low-level
talks and the signing of a number of bilateral cooperation
agreements.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
said Monday after talks with visiting Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides that relations between Greece and Turkey would never be
fully normalized unless there was a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
