<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Reportedly Quiet After Last Week's Attacks on U.N. Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The casualties among U.N. peacekeepers were all caused when the
lead vehicle in the Jordanian patrol took a direct hit from a
rocket-propelled grenade, Silva said.
</P>
<P>
According the spokesman, the Jordanians returned fire in self-
defense and obliterated the house from which the firing was coming,
killing at least 10 attackers.
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident later Friday night, Jordanian troops
deployed at Rokel Bridge were fired upon by a small group of
unidentified attackers and returned fire, and there were no
casualties within the U.N. Mission in Sierra Leone, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Silva said Sierra Leone rebels had stepped up executions, rape
and recruitment of child fighters.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said information from civilians fleeing areas
controlled by the rebel RUF indicated "recent fighting had been
accompanied by a rise in human rights violations".
</P>
<P>
The violations included "summary executions, rape and sexual
abuse, and the recruitment of child soldiers," he said.
</P>
<P>
There was no change in the 222 Indian peacekeepers and 11
military observers who are surrounded by the RUF in Kailahun, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
A ceasefire faltered earlier this year when U.N. peacekeepers
moved too close to diamond-mining areas the rebels controlled. The
RUF took hostage some 500 U.N. troops, which they have since
released, and besieged 233 others, which they have still not
allowed to leave from their surrounded base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
