<HEADLINE> Former IMF Director Calls L. America to Fight Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Managing Director of
International Monetary Fund ( IFM) Michael Camdessus called Monday
on Latin America to fight against poverty through excellence in
political measures and a deep restructuring of resource
redistribution criteria.
</P>
<P>
In his dissertation at Argentine-European Union Forum,
Camdessus said that Latin America "holds the world record for
inequality," speaking at the opening of an Argentine-European
Union meeting.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus told the some 500 business leaders at the meeting
here that inequality was so high there because "we have failed in
the distribution of resources."
</P>
<P>
The French economist also emphasized the positive effects of
globalization, saying that there is no reversal possible in the
process of world integration.
</P>
<P>
Poverty is the main risk and the most important for the world,
Camdessus said, stressing the necessity to "give social responses"
and at the same time defending openness to the flux of
international capital.
</P>
<P>
Latin America has left behind years of protectionism and paid
an important social cost, Machinea said.
</P>
<P>
Being 13-year IMF director, he admitted that globalizing still
had assignments awaiting that mustn't be forgotten, and countries
have to work on this question to achieve a solid macroeconomic
framework and consolidating of the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Without rules, it's imprudent to enter the turbulent waters of
globalization. Governments should assume responsibility to enforce
rules, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
